1
00:00:59,962 --> 00:01:02,006
[whistle being blown in distance]

2
00:01:02,047 --> 00:01:04,216
-[horns honking and chatter]
-[man] Yo, Tommy!

3
00:01:04,258 --> 00:01:06,302
[man whistles] Hey, taxi!

4
00:01:12,725 --> 00:01:15,478
-[upbeat band music playing]
-Cigars. Cigarettes.

5
00:01:15,519 --> 00:01:17,688
[chatter and laughter]

6
00:01:17,730 --> 00:01:19,315
[man] Hey, great idea.

7
00:01:22,067 --> 00:01:26,238
Hello, New York.
I'm Bobby Rydell and I'm glad to be here!

8
00:01:29,450 --> 00:01:31,577
[Bobby] Thank you all
for coming to see us tonight.

9
00:01:31,619 --> 00:01:33,662
It's Saturday night at the Copa!

10
00:01:34,288 --> 00:01:36,624
We think you're gonna have
a great time tonight.

11
00:01:36,665 --> 00:01:39,043
We're gonna do our best
to make sure of that.

12
00:01:39,085 --> 00:01:43,089
As always, a very special thanks
to Mr Jules Podell for having us out.

13
00:01:43,714 --> 00:01:45,382
Let's get started.

14
00:01:46,926 --> 00:01:51,222
<i>♪ That old black magic has me
In its spell ♪</i>

15
00:01:51,263 --> 00:01:56,060
<i>♪ That old black magic
That you, uh, weave so well ♪</i>

16
00:01:56,102 --> 00:02:00,606
<i>♪ Those icy fingers
Up and down my spine ♪</i>

17
00:02:00,648 --> 00:02:03,943
<i>♪ The same old witchcraft
When your eyes meet mine ♪</i>

18
00:02:03,984 --> 00:02:05,736
<i>♪ I love them so well ♪</i>

19
00:02:05,778 --> 00:02:07,947
<i>-♪ That same old tingle... ♪</i>
-[woman] Cigars?

20
00:02:07,988 --> 00:02:10,116
<i>♪ That I feel inside ♪</i>

21
00:02:10,157 --> 00:02:14,453
<i>♪ And then that elevator
Starts its ride ♪</i>

22
00:02:14,495 --> 00:02:15,579
<i>♪ Darling... ♪</i>

23
00:02:16,329 --> 00:02:17,873
Hello, sweetheart.

24
00:02:17,915 --> 00:02:20,835
Here's my coat. And you see this here hat?

25
00:02:20,876 --> 00:02:25,131
I want you to guard it with your life.
It was a gift from my mother.

26
00:02:25,172 --> 00:02:28,592
-Yes, Mr Loscudo.
-[Loscudo] Here, that's for you.

27
00:02:29,802 --> 00:02:32,513
-Thank you, sir.
-[man] Gio!

28
00:02:32,555 --> 00:02:36,475
-Hey, Carmine. How are you, pally?
-Good to see you.

29
00:02:36,517 --> 00:02:40,354
-Oh, thank you. That's unnecessary.
-Come on, let's go. <i>Andiamo.</i>

30
00:02:40,396 --> 00:02:43,566
I saw this kid, Bobby Rydell,
two and a half years ago in South Philly.

31
00:02:43,607 --> 00:02:45,067
Nobody knew who he was.

32
00:02:45,109 --> 00:02:47,111
[Carmine] They know him now.

33
00:02:47,153 --> 00:02:49,572
Hey, give me Loscudo's hat.

34
00:02:49,613 --> 00:02:51,365
-But he said to guard it.
-I know. I heard.

35
00:02:52,283 --> 00:02:54,785
Give it to me, all right? Come on.

36
00:02:54,827 --> 00:02:57,204
[Bobby] <i>♪ Yeah, I should stay away ♪</i>

37
00:02:57,246 --> 00:02:59,457
<i>♪ But what can I do? ♪</i>

38
00:02:59,498 --> 00:03:01,709
<i>♪ I hear your name... ♪</i>

39
00:03:01,751 --> 00:03:05,588
-Hey, be respectful, and watch your mouth.
-Shut up. She works here, tough guy.

40
00:03:05,629 --> 00:03:07,840
-Yeah, what are you gonna do?
-[grunting]

41
00:03:09,383 --> 00:03:11,886
-[woman screams]
-Tony Lip!

42
00:03:11,927 --> 00:03:13,888
[thudding and clattering]

43
00:03:13,929 --> 00:03:18,809
<i>♪ Well, now you're the lover
I have waited for ♪</i>

44
00:03:18,851 --> 00:03:23,439
<i>♪ You're the mate
That fate had me created for ♪</i>

45
00:03:23,481 --> 00:03:27,568
<i>♪ And every time
your lips meet mine, yow... ♪</i>

46
00:03:27,610 --> 00:03:29,987
[grunting and groaning]

47
00:03:30,029 --> 00:03:31,655
[bystanders muttering]

48
00:03:32,323 --> 00:03:33,449
[man grunts]

49
00:03:35,117 --> 00:03:36,869
You put your hands on me, you punk?

50
00:03:36,911 --> 00:03:38,954
Do yourself a favor,
go home with your friends.

51
00:03:38,996 --> 00:03:41,499
You don't tell me where to go.
You know who I am?

52
00:03:41,540 --> 00:03:43,125
I'm going back in there.

53
00:03:44,668 --> 00:03:46,670
-[grunting]
-[onlookers gasp]

54
00:03:46,712 --> 00:03:49,340
<i>♪ Under that old black magic
called love ♪</i>

55
00:03:50,424 --> 00:03:52,760
<i>♪ Keep talking about
That black old magic ♪</i>

56
00:03:52,802 --> 00:03:56,055
<i>♪ Yeah, baby, cos I love, oh, yeah
Love that thing ♪</i>

57
00:03:56,097 --> 00:04:00,101
<i>♪ Old black magic ♪</i>

58
00:04:00,142 --> 00:04:06,023
<i>♪ Yeah, love ♪</i>

59
00:04:06,982 --> 00:04:09,026
[cheering and applause]

60
00:04:10,027 --> 00:04:11,612
You tell Juley Podell,

61
00:04:11,654 --> 00:04:14,406
if I don't get my hat,
I'm gonna burn this joint down! Hear me?

62
00:04:14,448 --> 00:04:16,408
Joe, it's gonna turn up.
I swear it'll turn up.

63
00:04:16,450 --> 00:04:18,911
-Really? You tell that fat Jew bastard...
-It'll turn up.

64
00:04:18,953 --> 00:04:21,122
I don't get my hat,
I'll burn the Copa down!

65
00:04:26,335 --> 00:04:29,046
I'm gonna have to go back
to driving garbage trucks.

66
00:04:29,713 --> 00:04:33,926
Jesus Christ. Loscudo's out of his mind.

67
00:04:36,011 --> 00:04:38,347
-Mm-hm.
-We earned our money tonight.

68
00:04:38,389 --> 00:04:40,224
Lip, I thought
you were gonna kill that guy.

69
00:04:40,266 --> 00:04:42,309
-Yeah.
-Better him than me.

70
00:04:44,186 --> 00:04:46,689
So what are you gonna do
while we're closed?

71
00:04:46,730 --> 00:04:49,859
I don't know.
Maybe go work at my uncle's pizza joint.

72
00:04:51,652 --> 00:04:54,280
-You?
-I'm gonna drink for two months.

73
00:04:54,321 --> 00:04:56,782
-[door squeaking open]
-[Tony chuckles]

74
00:05:00,369 --> 00:05:03,372
-Take me home, Lip.
-Hey, good luck.

75
00:05:03,414 --> 00:05:04,832
-You, too.
-See you, Carmine.

76
00:05:04,874 --> 00:05:07,752
-No, that should not happen. Well...
-No, I don't want to be a--

77
00:05:09,670 --> 00:05:10,755
My hat!

78
00:05:12,047 --> 00:05:15,509
Heard it was missing, so I looked into it.

79
00:05:15,551 --> 00:05:17,428
I wanted to kill that broad.

80
00:05:17,470 --> 00:05:21,557
-No, no. It wasn't her fault.
-Who had the balls to clip Gio's hat?

81
00:05:22,224 --> 00:05:25,686
-Don't worry about it. I took care of it.
-Yeah, I hope you gave him some beating.

82
00:05:27,229 --> 00:05:29,565
Here. Take this. Put it in your kick.

83
00:05:30,274 --> 00:05:33,611
No, no, thanks.
It was a pleasure, Mr Loscudo, really.

84
00:05:33,652 --> 00:05:35,154
Bullshit. Take it.

85
00:05:36,071 --> 00:05:40,117
And from now on, you don't call me
Mr Loscudo. You hear me?

86
00:05:40,159 --> 00:05:42,870
-I'm your pal Gio.
-[chuckles]

87
00:05:47,708 --> 00:05:49,752
["One Mint Julep" by The Clovers]

88
00:05:50,461 --> 00:05:52,505
<i>♪ One early morning ♪</i>

89
00:05:53,005 --> 00:05:55,049
<i>♪ As I was walking ♪</i>

90
00:05:55,091 --> 00:05:57,301
<i>♪ I met a woman ♪</i>

91
00:05:57,343 --> 00:05:59,637
<i>♪ We started talking ♪</i>

92
00:05:59,678 --> 00:06:04,433
<i>♪ I took her home to get a few nips ♪</i>

93
00:06:04,475 --> 00:06:08,187
<i>♪ But all I had was a mint julep ♪</i>

94
00:06:08,229 --> 00:06:10,773
<i>♪ One mint julep ♪</i>

95
00:06:10,815 --> 00:06:14,860
<i>♪ Was the cause of it all ♪</i>

96
00:06:16,570 --> 00:06:17,822
<i>♪ Ooh-ooh ♪</i>

97
00:06:17,863 --> 00:06:21,158
<i>♪ I don't remember just how it started ♪</i>

98
00:06:21,200 --> 00:06:24,161
-[sighs, sniffs]
<i>-♪ But all I know is ♪</i>

99
00:06:24,203 --> 00:06:26,705
-[sighs]
<i>-♪ We should have parted ♪</i>

100
00:06:26,747 --> 00:06:31,210
<i>♪ I stole a kiss and then another ♪</i>

101
00:06:31,252 --> 00:06:35,548
<i>-♪ I didn't mean to take it further ♪</i>
-[sighs]

102
00:06:35,589 --> 00:06:42,012
<i>♪ One mint julep
Was the cause of it all ♪</i>

103
00:06:43,597 --> 00:06:48,352
<i>♪ The lights were burning low
There in the parlor ♪</i>

104
00:06:48,394 --> 00:06:52,982
<i>♪ When through the kitchen door
Up popped her father ♪</i>

105
00:06:53,023 --> 00:06:57,319
<i>♪ He said I saw you when
You kissed my daughter ♪</i>

106
00:06:57,361 --> 00:07:02,199
<i>♪ Gotta wed her right now
Or face a slaughter ♪</i>

107
00:07:02,241 --> 00:07:04,827
-<i>♪ One mint julep ♪</i>
-[grunts]

108
00:07:04,869 --> 00:07:06,579
<i>♪ Was the cause of it all ♪</i>

109
00:07:06,620 --> 00:07:09,457
-Morning.
-Good night. [sighs]

110
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:13,043
[TV] <i>One down,
and the batter will be Roger Maris.</i>

111
00:07:13,085 --> 00:07:15,254
-[man] We need to get back in this.
<i>-The pitch-curveball...</i>

112
00:07:15,296 --> 00:07:17,965
[man] Come on, Roger. Come on.

113
00:07:18,007 --> 00:07:20,593
Come on, Roger, hit one out! Let's do it!

114
00:07:20,634 --> 00:07:23,012
-Johnny, quiet. You're gonna jinx it.
-Come on, Roger.

115
00:07:23,053 --> 00:07:25,222
Hey, Johnny. Think you could yell louder?

116
00:07:25,264 --> 00:07:27,558
-Maris is up.
-Yeah, so am I now.

117
00:07:29,101 --> 00:07:33,314
-What the hell all you guys doing here?
-We came over to keep Dolores company.

118
00:07:34,690 --> 00:07:36,984
[commentary in background]

119
00:07:37,026 --> 00:07:38,402
-Come on.
-Tony!

120
00:07:38,444 --> 00:07:40,696
[in Italian]

121
00:07:52,083 --> 00:07:53,793
Thank you, ma'am.

122
00:07:53,834 --> 00:07:55,211
[commentary in background]

123
00:07:58,798 --> 00:08:02,093
-Come on, Roger, please.
-Let's do it, baby.

124
00:08:02,134 --> 00:08:03,928
-I'll walk you out.
-Sure.

125
00:08:05,054 --> 00:08:07,306
-We need to get back in this ball game.
-Come on.

126
00:08:07,348 --> 00:08:09,600
-Thank you so much.
-Any problems, give us a call.

127
00:08:09,642 --> 00:08:11,102
-[clapping]
-Come on, Roger.

128
00:08:11,143 --> 00:08:12,561
<i>-The one-two pitch.</i>
-Come on!

129
00:08:12,603 --> 00:08:15,773
<i>-It's hit deep into right field...</i>
-[excited chatter]

130
00:08:15,815 --> 00:08:18,275
[all cheering]

131
00:08:18,317 --> 00:08:21,403
-Yes!
-We did it! We got it!

132
00:08:22,029 --> 00:08:24,281
-Yeah! Whoo!
-There it is!

133
00:08:24,323 --> 00:08:25,825
-All right.
-Three-one, baby.

134
00:08:25,866 --> 00:08:28,911
-Coming back.
-Roger, baby, way to go!

135
00:08:28,953 --> 00:08:30,538
-Three-one.
-Way to go!

136
00:08:31,705 --> 00:08:35,126
[Johnny] Do it again.
Let's do it again. Come on, baby.

137
00:08:35,167 --> 00:08:37,837
No, Tony. Go get dressed. We're gonna eat.

138
00:08:39,880 --> 00:08:42,842
-All right.
-No game seven, no game seven.

139
00:08:52,184 --> 00:08:53,978
[clinking]

140
00:08:54,019 --> 00:08:57,314
[Dolores] ...from thy bounty,
through Christ, our Lord. Amen.

141
00:08:57,356 --> 00:08:58,774
[others] Amen.

142
00:09:00,067 --> 00:09:02,945
And if anyone hears of a job for Tony,
let us know.

143
00:09:02,987 --> 00:09:04,613
-Dolor.
-What?

144
00:09:04,655 --> 00:09:06,115
Please.

145
00:09:06,157 --> 00:09:09,034
-What happened? You get fired?
-No.

146
00:09:09,076 --> 00:09:12,747
No. The Copa's closing for repairs, so
he needs something for a couple of months.

147
00:09:12,788 --> 00:09:16,208
[in Italian]

148
00:09:21,547 --> 00:09:24,383
All the people he knows,
he'll find something in no time.

149
00:09:24,425 --> 00:09:27,553
Well, he had a great job
at the Sanitation Department.

150
00:09:27,595 --> 00:09:29,388
You shouldn't have
punched out the foreman.

151
00:09:30,473 --> 00:09:33,225
-He shouldn't have woke me up.
-[laughter]

152
00:09:33,267 --> 00:09:35,561
That's Tony.

153
00:09:35,603 --> 00:09:37,480
I can't believe they lost.

154
00:09:37,521 --> 00:09:39,064
-Don't worry.
-Relax.

155
00:09:39,106 --> 00:09:41,192
[lively chatter]

156
00:09:43,194 --> 00:09:47,114
That never happened before.
They're gonna win the World Series.

157
00:09:47,156 --> 00:09:49,825
[chatter continues]

158
00:09:55,039 --> 00:09:57,708
I'm telling you,
this is gonna be the easiest 50 bucks

159
00:09:57,750 --> 00:09:59,585
-you ever gonna make.
-Yeah, we'll see.

160
00:10:00,419 --> 00:10:03,672
Hey, there they are. Hi, Johnny.

161
00:10:03,714 --> 00:10:05,132
-Tony, how are you?
-Hey, Paulie.

162
00:10:05,174 --> 00:10:07,009
-How you doing?
-I'm good, I'm good.

163
00:10:07,051 --> 00:10:11,013
So Johnny here tells me you ate 48
White Castle burgers all in one sitting.

164
00:10:11,055 --> 00:10:14,391
-Cheeseburgers.
-You tell him, Frankie.

165
00:10:14,433 --> 00:10:15,601
I don't believe it.

166
00:10:15,643 --> 00:10:19,105
What do we care if you believe it?
Hey, Gorman.

167
00:10:19,146 --> 00:10:23,692
-What's the record here for hot dogs?
-Eighteen. Fat Paulie.

168
00:10:23,734 --> 00:10:27,780
-Why wasn't Lip in on that contest?
-What contest? I was hungry.

169
00:10:27,822 --> 00:10:29,824
-[chuckling]
-[Gorman] The bet's simple.

170
00:10:29,865 --> 00:10:32,368
Half a C-note.
Most hot dogs in an hour wins.

171
00:10:32,409 --> 00:10:33,828
With toppings.

172
00:10:35,704 --> 00:10:37,915
-What the hell you weigh?
-Two sixty.

173
00:10:37,957 --> 00:10:40,042
Hey, two-- Your left ass weighs 260.

174
00:10:40,084 --> 00:10:42,670
May my mother-in-law drop dead
on the spot if I'm lying.

175
00:10:42,711 --> 00:10:44,672
[chuckling]

176
00:10:46,090 --> 00:10:47,758
-All right. You're on.
-Good.

177
00:10:50,136 --> 00:10:54,265
Pick it up, Lip!
The baby elephant just hit 19!

178
00:10:54,306 --> 00:10:56,183
Let's go, Lip! Let's go!

179
00:10:56,225 --> 00:10:58,436
Come on, let's go, Lip!
Let's get this going!

180
00:10:58,477 --> 00:11:00,354
You're embarrassing!

181
00:11:00,396 --> 00:11:02,731
You're embarrassing your son!

182
00:11:02,773 --> 00:11:04,733
He is killing you!

183
00:11:08,112 --> 00:11:09,447
[Tony groans]

184
00:11:12,324 --> 00:11:14,076
Hey, Nicky, you doing your homework?

185
00:11:14,118 --> 00:11:15,661
-Yep.
-Good.

186
00:11:15,703 --> 00:11:18,497
-[Tony groans]
-Where you been?

187
00:11:19,415 --> 00:11:21,834
-Gorman's.
-I'm making dinner.

188
00:11:22,752 --> 00:11:24,837
[sighs]

189
00:11:24,879 --> 00:11:27,840
Fat Paulie bet me 50 bucks
he could eat more hot dogs than me.

190
00:11:27,882 --> 00:11:31,093
He knocked off 24. Guy's an animal.

191
00:11:31,135 --> 00:11:34,096
Are you crazy? You lost $50?

192
00:11:34,138 --> 00:11:36,182
Dolores, please.

193
00:11:38,100 --> 00:11:39,477
I ate 26.

194
00:11:45,107 --> 00:11:47,943
You are so lucky. You know that?

195
00:11:47,985 --> 00:11:49,945
-[Tony chuckles]
-Rent is due on Monday.

196
00:11:49,987 --> 00:11:53,574
-[chuckles]
-[phone ringing]

197
00:11:55,284 --> 00:11:56,452
You gonna get that?

198
00:11:57,912 --> 00:12:01,123
-[sighs] Yeah?
-[Jules] <i>Hey, Lip.</i>

199
00:12:01,165 --> 00:12:05,044
Some guy called over here.
A doctor. He's looking for a driver.

200
00:12:05,086 --> 00:12:06,837
-You interested?
<i>-Yeah.</i>

201
00:12:06,879 --> 00:12:09,882
They're interviewing guys
tomorrow afternoon.

202
00:12:09,924 --> 00:12:13,094
The address is, uh... 881,

203
00:12:13,135 --> 00:12:16,263
<i>7th Avenue, 2:15.</i>

204
00:12:18,349 --> 00:12:20,392
[chatter]

205
00:12:36,408 --> 00:12:39,286
-Hey. Excuse me.
-We're not open right now.

206
00:12:39,328 --> 00:12:41,831
But you're welcome to purchase tickets
to tonight's performance.

207
00:12:41,872 --> 00:12:44,208
Nah, that's all right. I, uh...

208
00:12:44,250 --> 00:12:48,212
I think I got the wrong address, but...
Is there a doctor's office in here?

209
00:12:48,254 --> 00:12:51,298
-A doctor's office?
-Dr Shirley?

210
00:12:51,340 --> 00:12:55,219
Oh. You have the correct address.
Dr Shirley lives upstairs, above the Hall.

211
00:12:59,306 --> 00:13:02,435
[sighs] How you doing?

212
00:13:12,778 --> 00:13:15,239
[clears throat]
I'm here for the driver job.

213
00:13:16,449 --> 00:13:17,700
Tony Lip.

214
00:13:22,204 --> 00:13:25,332
-No, I should be on there.
-Uh...

215
00:13:26,167 --> 00:13:30,713
No. Um, I have
a Tony Val-- Vallelala--

216
00:13:30,755 --> 00:13:32,673
Vallelonga. Yeah. That's me.

217
00:13:35,217 --> 00:13:37,261
-Fill it out while you wait.
-What?

218
00:13:37,303 --> 00:13:39,638
Fill it out while you wait.

219
00:13:39,680 --> 00:13:41,265
-Oh. Yeah.
-[clicks fingers]

220
00:13:48,439 --> 00:13:50,149
[Tony grunts]

221
00:14:03,954 --> 00:14:04,955
Have a seat.

222
00:14:18,135 --> 00:14:20,846
[bells chiming nearby]

223
00:14:24,892 --> 00:14:28,020
-[distant door opens and closes]
-[footsteps approaching]

224
00:14:33,359 --> 00:14:34,985
Mr Vallelonga.

225
00:14:35,027 --> 00:14:37,238
-Sorry to keep you waiting.
-Oh.

226
00:14:38,447 --> 00:14:40,783
-[grunts]
-I'm Dr Donald Shirley.

227
00:14:41,492 --> 00:14:44,453
-Tony.
-Yes. Please sit down.

228
00:14:46,080 --> 00:14:47,832
[chains rattling]

229
00:14:48,499 --> 00:14:50,376
Some place you got here. [chuckles]

230
00:14:51,460 --> 00:14:54,755
-Are them horns real?
-Elephant tusks, yes.

231
00:14:56,674 --> 00:14:59,176
What about that? Is that a molar?

232
00:15:01,429 --> 00:15:04,348
-A what?
-A molar, like a, like a shark tooth.

233
00:15:05,099 --> 00:15:08,436
-Or a tiger's, maybe.
-It was a gift.

234
00:15:09,520 --> 00:15:12,731
I thought, uh...
I thought I was going to an office.

235
00:15:12,773 --> 00:15:15,025
They said a doctor needed a driver.

236
00:15:15,776 --> 00:15:17,278
That's all they told you?

237
00:15:17,319 --> 00:15:18,362
-Yeah.
-[chuckles]

238
00:15:18,404 --> 00:15:20,781
Actually,
it's a bit more complicated than that.

239
00:15:22,366 --> 00:15:24,535
Have you ever driven
professionally before?

240
00:15:25,745 --> 00:15:28,914
Yeah. Sanitation. Garbage trucks.

241
00:15:29,874 --> 00:15:31,834
Plus, I drive my boss home at night.

242
00:15:31,876 --> 00:15:35,421
But I can drive anything.
Limos. Tow trucks.

243
00:15:36,088 --> 00:15:38,507
-Snowplows. Whatever.
-I see.

244
00:15:38,549 --> 00:15:42,011
-What other experience do you have?
-I worked a lot of joints.

245
00:15:42,052 --> 00:15:44,388
Wagon Wheel, Peppermint Lounge, Copa.

246
00:15:44,430 --> 00:15:47,349
-In what capacity?
-What do you mean?

247
00:15:47,933 --> 00:15:50,895
-What did you do there?
-Uh...

248
00:15:52,354 --> 00:15:53,856
Public relations.

249
00:15:55,024 --> 00:15:58,778
Well, first of all, Tony,
I'm not a medical doctor, I'm a musician.

250
00:15:59,612 --> 00:16:02,364
-You mean, like, songs?
-Yes.

251
00:16:02,406 --> 00:16:06,202
And I'm about to embark on a concert tour,
the majority of which will be down south.

252
00:16:06,243 --> 00:16:07,536
Atlantic City.

253
00:16:07,578 --> 00:16:10,331
No. The Deep South.

254
00:16:10,372 --> 00:16:14,043
First, we're starting in the Midwest
and then we're taking a hard left.

255
00:16:14,085 --> 00:16:17,797
Kentucky, North Carolina, Tennessee,
and on down through the Delta.

256
00:16:17,838 --> 00:16:20,883
Do you foresee any issues
in working for a black man?

257
00:16:21,717 --> 00:16:22,718
No.

258
00:16:23,636 --> 00:16:26,680
No, no, no. It was just the other day,

259
00:16:26,722 --> 00:16:29,391
me and the wife had a couple
of colored guys over at the house.

260
00:16:30,643 --> 00:16:32,728
For, for drinks.

261
00:16:32,770 --> 00:16:35,356
Hmm. I see. You're married.

262
00:16:35,397 --> 00:16:37,691
Yeah. Two kids.

263
00:16:39,735 --> 00:16:42,196
I'm not sure this is the proper job
for a married man.

264
00:16:42,238 --> 00:16:44,156
Why? Are we bringing broads?

265
00:16:45,116 --> 00:16:48,202
My point is
we'll be gone for eight straight weeks.

266
00:16:48,244 --> 00:16:50,413
No breaks, right up until Christmas.

267
00:16:50,454 --> 00:16:53,165
You're quite sure
you can leave your family for that long?

268
00:16:53,207 --> 00:16:55,918
-Depends what you're paying.
-A hundred dollars a week.

269
00:16:55,960 --> 00:16:57,962
-Plus room and board.
-Hmm.

270
00:16:58,003 --> 00:17:02,174
But let me be crystal clear.
I'm not just hiring a chauffeur.

271
00:17:03,217 --> 00:17:05,344
I need someone
who can handle my itinerary.

272
00:17:05,386 --> 00:17:07,847
Be a personal assistant. I need a valet.

273
00:17:08,472 --> 00:17:11,851
I need someone who can launder my clothes
and shine my shoes.

274
00:17:14,353 --> 00:17:15,646
Good luck, Doc.

275
00:17:18,731 --> 00:17:19,733
Tony.

276
00:17:25,364 --> 00:17:28,825
I had my record label ask around town
to find me the right man.

277
00:17:28,868 --> 00:17:30,995
Your name came up more than once.

278
00:17:32,412 --> 00:17:34,665
You've impressed several people
with your...

279
00:17:35,791 --> 00:17:37,501
innate ability to handle trouble.

280
00:17:38,961 --> 00:17:42,256
And that is why I called
and enquired about your availability.

281
00:17:46,051 --> 00:17:49,472
Okay, here's the deal. I got no problem
being on the road with you.

282
00:17:49,513 --> 00:17:52,266
But I ain't no butler.
I ain't ironing no shirts

283
00:17:52,308 --> 00:17:53,976
and I'm not polishing nobody's shoes.

284
00:17:54,018 --> 00:17:56,103
You need somebody to get you
from point A to point B

285
00:17:56,145 --> 00:17:58,314
and to make sure there's
no problems along the way?

286
00:17:58,355 --> 00:18:02,318
And believe me, you, in the Deep South...
there's gonna be problems.

287
00:18:03,277 --> 00:18:06,071
So if you want me,
it's a buck and a quarter a week.

288
00:18:06,113 --> 00:18:09,617
Or go hire that little Chink just pranced
out of here, see how far you get.

289
00:18:12,620 --> 00:18:14,288
Well, Mr Vallelonga...

290
00:18:15,915 --> 00:18:17,708
thank you for stopping by.

291
00:18:17,750 --> 00:18:21,212
["Throw It Out Of Your Mind"
by Timmy Shaw]

292
00:18:22,463 --> 00:18:24,590
[chatter]

293
00:18:30,054 --> 00:18:31,597
Hey, Bobby.

294
00:18:32,515 --> 00:18:35,059
Give me a Rheingold. Ice cold.

295
00:18:36,143 --> 00:18:38,145
-[song continues]
-[chatter]

296
00:18:44,652 --> 00:18:45,694
Mr Tony.

297
00:18:47,238 --> 00:18:49,115
Augie asking about you.

298
00:18:50,074 --> 00:18:52,409
[slaps bar] Come on!
I'm dying of thirst over here.

299
00:18:52,451 --> 00:18:54,912
Shut up! I'm talking.

300
00:18:58,791 --> 00:19:01,669
-When?
-Now. He in his box.

301
00:19:22,731 --> 00:19:24,316
[knocks]

302
00:19:28,154 --> 00:19:29,113
Tony Lip.

303
00:19:31,115 --> 00:19:34,785
What the hell happened at the Copa?
I hear you almost split a guy's face open.

304
00:19:36,328 --> 00:19:40,624
That guy you hit, Mikey Cerrone,
part of Charlie the Hand's crew.

305
00:19:41,876 --> 00:19:43,544
Guess he should've known better.

306
00:19:46,380 --> 00:19:50,092
[sighs] Hand asked me to look into it.

307
00:19:50,801 --> 00:19:55,639
I spoke to Podell. Whole thing was,
uh... over a piece of ass, right?

308
00:19:56,807 --> 00:19:57,808
Yeah.

309
00:19:58,642 --> 00:20:01,896
Beef like that should never happen
inside the club.

310
00:20:02,688 --> 00:20:04,064
They were out of line.

311
00:20:05,149 --> 00:20:06,525
So we squashed it.

312
00:20:08,611 --> 00:20:11,697
You, uh, looking to earn
a little extra scharole?

313
00:20:11,739 --> 00:20:14,158
I can keep you busy
while the Copa is down.

314
00:20:15,075 --> 00:20:16,452
What I gotta do?

315
00:20:17,953 --> 00:20:19,205
Things.

316
00:20:22,541 --> 00:20:26,420
Appreciate it, but, uh...
I want to spend some time with the family.

317
00:20:27,129 --> 00:20:30,216
Don't be stupid.
You make yourself a few extra bucks,

318
00:20:30,257 --> 00:20:33,803
you buy something nice
for that pretty little wife of yours.

319
00:20:34,512 --> 00:20:35,471
Hmm.

320
00:20:38,224 --> 00:20:41,352
Nah, I'm good. I'm flush right now.

321
00:20:42,937 --> 00:20:47,483
[The Blue Jays]
<i>♪ So long, Lover's Island ♪</i>

322
00:20:47,525 --> 00:20:49,860
<i>♪ Dee ♪
♪ Dee-ooh ♪</i>

323
00:20:49,902 --> 00:20:52,279
<i>♪ Ee, ah, ooh, ay... ♪</i>

324
00:20:52,321 --> 00:20:53,989
[song continues quietly]

325
00:20:55,741 --> 00:20:59,703
Here's 50. Here.
Pay me 60 by New Year's, you get it back.

326
00:21:03,124 --> 00:21:04,291
Hey, Lip.

327
00:21:05,626 --> 00:21:07,002
Everything okay?

328
00:21:07,878 --> 00:21:09,588
What, you got beak trouble, Charlie?

329
00:21:10,798 --> 00:21:12,299
Mind your business.

330
00:21:13,342 --> 00:21:16,220
<i>-♪ So long, Lover's Island </i>♪
-[door opens]

331
00:21:16,262 --> 00:21:19,557
So come on. I'm dying to hear.
What happened with the doctor interview?

332
00:21:20,349 --> 00:21:23,144
He ain't a real doctor.
He's a piano player.

333
00:21:24,103 --> 00:21:26,730
Well, I don't understand.
Why did they say that he was a doctor?

334
00:21:27,606 --> 00:21:31,277
I don't know. I think he's, like, a doctor
of, uh, piano playing or something.

335
00:21:31,318 --> 00:21:33,946
-You can be that?
-I guess.

336
00:21:34,655 --> 00:21:36,657
He lives on top of Carnegie Hall.

337
00:21:36,699 --> 00:21:38,409
You should've seen this place, Dee.

338
00:21:38,451 --> 00:21:41,162
It was filled with statues
and all kinds of fancy crap.

339
00:21:41,203 --> 00:21:43,414
And he was sitting
on top of a friggin' throne

340
00:21:43,456 --> 00:21:46,083
all dressed up
like the king of the jungle bunnies.

341
00:21:47,126 --> 00:21:48,419
He's colored?

342
00:21:50,087 --> 00:21:53,674
[scoffs softly]
Well, you wouldn't last a week with him.

343
00:21:53,716 --> 00:21:55,342
For the right money, I would.

344
00:21:56,302 --> 00:21:59,472
-[Tony snoring]
-[phone ringing]

345
00:22:03,058 --> 00:22:04,894
[groans]

346
00:22:04,935 --> 00:22:07,146
[sighs] Yeah.

347
00:22:08,564 --> 00:22:09,607
Oh.

348
00:22:10,357 --> 00:22:12,026
Look... [clears throat]

349
00:22:12,818 --> 00:22:15,362
Really? Uh, okay.

350
00:22:15,404 --> 00:22:17,114
-Everything okay?
-Okay, hang on a sec.

351
00:22:17,907 --> 00:22:21,327
It's, uh, Dr Shirley, the piano guy.

352
00:22:21,368 --> 00:22:23,287
He wants to talk to you.

353
00:22:23,329 --> 00:22:24,997
-Me?
-Yeah.

354
00:22:25,039 --> 00:22:27,833
-What? No.
-Come on.

355
00:22:27,875 --> 00:22:29,251
-Take it.
-No. Tony...

356
00:22:29,293 --> 00:22:30,628
Just, just talk.

357
00:22:34,215 --> 00:22:35,341
Hello?

358
00:22:37,927 --> 00:22:40,638
[chuckles] Uh, good morning,
Doctor, It's nice to talk to you.

359
00:22:45,893 --> 00:22:48,604
Well, uh, yes, that is a long time.

360
00:22:51,482 --> 00:22:52,650
It is.

361
00:22:55,027 --> 00:22:56,779
Yes. I'm sure.

362
00:22:56,821 --> 00:22:58,697
[faintly over phone] <i>Thank you.</i>

363
00:22:58,739 --> 00:23:01,033
Thank you for calling.

364
00:23:01,075 --> 00:23:02,368
Bye, now.

365
00:23:05,913 --> 00:23:06,831
What'd he say?

366
00:23:08,416 --> 00:23:10,376
He wanted to know if I'd be okay

367
00:23:10,418 --> 00:23:13,921
with him taking my husband away
from his family for two months.

368
00:23:15,881 --> 00:23:17,883
He said he'd pay you what you asked for.

369
00:23:20,886 --> 00:23:22,138
[Tony grunts]

370
00:23:23,681 --> 00:23:25,391
-Hey.
-Hmm?

371
00:23:27,309 --> 00:23:30,229
It's good money. We need it.

372
00:23:33,441 --> 00:23:36,944
Can't be eating 26 hot dogs every day.

373
00:23:38,863 --> 00:23:40,739
I know. [sniffles]

374
00:23:41,532 --> 00:23:43,909
I told him it was okay for you to go.

375
00:23:46,620 --> 00:23:49,081
All right, hey, look,
so here's the first half of your pay.

376
00:23:49,123 --> 00:23:52,418
-You'll get the rest when the tour's over.
-No, I gotta get paid every week.

377
00:23:52,460 --> 00:23:54,503
Sorry, that's not
how the record company does it.

378
00:23:54,545 --> 00:23:56,756
We gotta have some guarantee
you'll finish the job.

379
00:23:57,339 --> 00:23:59,633
Why wouldn't I finish the job?
I took it, didn't I?

380
00:23:59,675 --> 00:24:02,052
Well, then we got nothing to worry about.

381
00:24:03,220 --> 00:24:06,223
Here's the deal, Mr Vallelonga.

382
00:24:06,265 --> 00:24:08,893
Okay, it's your job to get Don
to all his tour dates on time.

383
00:24:08,934 --> 00:24:11,312
If he misses any shows,
you're not getting your back end.

384
00:24:11,353 --> 00:24:13,063
-He's not gonna miss any show.
-Good.

385
00:24:13,939 --> 00:24:15,608
Oh, you're gonna need this.

386
00:24:16,692 --> 00:24:18,360
This is the book I was telling you about.

387
00:24:18,402 --> 00:24:21,363
Sometimes you guys are staying
in the same hotel, sometimes you're not.

388
00:24:22,281 --> 00:24:24,533
-[Tony] Oh, yeah, the...
-[man] Yeah, yeah.

389
00:24:24,575 --> 00:24:26,869
All right, don't let me down. Let's go.

390
00:24:27,870 --> 00:24:29,997
[music in background]

391
00:24:35,503 --> 00:24:39,340
-Madonna, is this the new one?
-Yeah, the record company rented it.

392
00:24:39,381 --> 00:24:41,425
-Nice, huh?
-Beautiful.

393
00:24:41,467 --> 00:24:44,512
So what'd my sister have to say
about you being gone for three weeks?

394
00:24:44,553 --> 00:24:46,472
-Eight weeks.
-[scoffs]

395
00:24:46,514 --> 00:24:49,642
Ten to one, you slap this moolie out,
you come home in under a month.

396
00:24:49,683 --> 00:24:51,602
[swears in Italian]

397
00:24:51,644 --> 00:24:53,646
-[Dolores] Come here.
-[Tony] Boys, huddle up.

398
00:24:53,687 --> 00:24:55,940
-Say good-bye to your father.
-Frankie, Nicky. Come here.

399
00:24:56,732 --> 00:24:58,818
-All right. You gonna be good boys?
-Uh-huh.

400
00:24:58,859 --> 00:25:00,402
-You'll listen to your mother?
-Uh-huh.

401
00:25:00,444 --> 00:25:03,823
Yeah? All right, give me a kiss.
I'm counting on youse.

402
00:25:05,699 --> 00:25:07,493
-Don't go too far.
-We won't.

403
00:25:10,996 --> 00:25:14,375
-Did you go to the AAA for the maps?
-Yes. No. I mean,

404
00:25:14,417 --> 00:25:17,586
the record companies gave me the maps
and the itinerary. And this thing.

405
00:25:19,755 --> 00:25:21,882
"<i>The Negro Motorist's Green Book</i>."

406
00:25:21,924 --> 00:25:24,427
Yeah, it lists all the places
coloreds can stay down south.

407
00:25:24,468 --> 00:25:27,054
Like a, you know,
"traveling while black."

408
00:25:27,096 --> 00:25:28,806
"Traveling while black"?

409
00:25:28,848 --> 00:25:31,642
Yeah, if you're black
and you gotta travel for some reason.

410
00:25:31,684 --> 00:25:34,603
-Got a special book for that?
-I guess.

411
00:25:34,645 --> 00:25:37,481
-Did you pack the iron?
-I ain't lugging no iron, Dee.

412
00:25:37,523 --> 00:25:40,526
-How are you gonna press your pants?
-I'll put 'em under the mattress.

413
00:25:41,694 --> 00:25:44,989
I want you to write me a letter.
Every chance you get.

414
00:25:45,030 --> 00:25:47,533
-I can't write letters.
-Yes, you can.

415
00:25:47,575 --> 00:25:49,618
-I can't write!
-Take you five minutes. Promise.

416
00:25:49,660 --> 00:25:51,954
It's embarrassing.
It ain't gonna be no good.

417
00:25:51,996 --> 00:25:54,540
It's a lot cheaper
than calling long-distance, Tony.

418
00:25:55,124 --> 00:25:58,002
-Promise me you're gonna write.
-I promise.

419
00:26:00,504 --> 00:26:04,383
Dee, put this in the bank today.
It's half my pay.

420
00:26:04,425 --> 00:26:08,262
Oh, here. There's a couple of sandwiches
for you and Dr Shirley.

421
00:26:08,304 --> 00:26:09,388
Thanks.

422
00:26:09,430 --> 00:26:11,557
-Be careful.
-I will.

423
00:26:11,599 --> 00:26:14,769
-I love you.
-I love you, too, baby.

424
00:26:14,810 --> 00:26:17,563
["A Letter From My Baby" by Timmy Shaw]

425
00:26:19,648 --> 00:26:22,943
You better be home for Christmas,
or don't come home at all.

426
00:26:24,987 --> 00:26:27,948
[in Italian]

427
00:26:27,990 --> 00:26:30,159
I got it, Pop. I got it.

428
00:26:30,201 --> 00:26:33,120
<i>♪ I got a letter from my baby ♪</i>

429
00:26:33,788 --> 00:26:35,581
<i>♪ Mailman brought it today ♪</i>

430
00:26:36,957 --> 00:26:39,460
<i>♪ She said she's so sorry ♪</i>

431
00:26:40,503 --> 00:26:42,505
<i>♪ Uh, that she went away ♪</i>

432
00:26:43,881 --> 00:26:46,926
<i>♪ She said, Daddy, don't worry ♪</i>

433
00:26:47,510 --> 00:26:49,762
<i>♪ Because it won't be long ♪</i>

434
00:26:50,471 --> 00:26:53,057
<i>♪ Hey, before I'll be back home ♪</i>

435
00:26:54,183 --> 00:26:56,018
<i>♪ Oh, yeah ♪</i>

436
00:26:56,811 --> 00:26:58,604
Hey. I'm Tony.

437
00:26:59,730 --> 00:27:01,774
His driver. Bum a smoke?

438
00:27:07,488 --> 00:27:08,531
Thanks.

439
00:27:18,040 --> 00:27:19,458
So you're the band?

440
00:27:21,669 --> 00:27:23,421
[in Russian accent] Oleg. Cello.

441
00:27:24,213 --> 00:27:27,758
George. Bass.
And we're not a band. We're a trio.

442
00:27:28,384 --> 00:27:31,303
Oh. Trio. Right.

443
00:27:31,345 --> 00:27:34,014
-[Dr Shirley] Good morning. Excuse me.
-Morning.

444
00:27:48,988 --> 00:27:50,281
[groans]

445
00:27:58,998 --> 00:28:00,499
[Dr Shirley] Thank you, Amit.

446
00:28:01,625 --> 00:28:03,127
Have a wonderful trip, sir.

447
00:28:37,787 --> 00:28:42,041
["Goodbye, My Lover, Goodbye"
by Robert Mosely]

448
00:28:47,546 --> 00:28:52,051
<i>♪ Goodbye ♪</i>

449
00:28:55,096 --> 00:28:56,514
<i>♪ My love ♪</i>

450
00:28:57,640 --> 00:29:01,936
<i>♪ Goodbye </i>♪

451
00:29:02,770 --> 00:29:06,357
<i>♪ Goodbye, my love </i>♪

452
00:29:09,151 --> 00:29:11,987
<i>♪ Though I love you truly... </i>♪

453
00:29:12,029 --> 00:29:14,865
Tony, the first thing I'd like you to do
when we arrive in the city...

454
00:29:14,907 --> 00:29:16,784
-Hmm.
-...is check the piano where I'm playing.

455
00:29:16,826 --> 00:29:19,495
Make sure it's a Steinway
as per my contract.

456
00:29:19,537 --> 00:29:22,373
[song continues over radio]

457
00:29:22,415 --> 00:29:26,168
And can you see to it that there's
a bottle of Cutty Sark in my room?

458
00:29:26,210 --> 00:29:28,963
-Every night.
-Every night?

459
00:29:29,004 --> 00:29:30,965
[Tony chuckles]

460
00:29:31,006 --> 00:29:33,592
Well, if you ever need
any help with that...

461
00:29:33,634 --> 00:29:35,302
I won't.

462
00:29:37,513 --> 00:29:39,348
Ten and two on the wheel, please.

463
00:29:42,893 --> 00:29:43,936
Hey, Doc.

464
00:29:44,520 --> 00:29:49,316
I noticed on the itinerary thing,
the last show's on the 23rd of December.

465
00:29:49,358 --> 00:29:51,902
-Right?
-Birmingham, yes. It's a Christmas show.

466
00:29:51,944 --> 00:29:54,822
So any way we could, uh,
maybe hit the road early next morning

467
00:29:54,864 --> 00:29:56,782
so we'd be home in time for Christmas Eve?

468
00:29:56,824 --> 00:29:59,869
-We'll see.
-Appreciate it.

469
00:29:59,910 --> 00:30:02,955
[clears throat]
Could you put out the cigarette, please?

470
00:30:03,706 --> 00:30:04,707
Why?

471
00:30:05,666 --> 00:30:07,418
I can't breathe back here.

472
00:30:10,087 --> 00:30:12,673
What are you talking about?
Smoke's going in <i>my </i>lungs.

473
00:30:12,715 --> 00:30:14,842
-I'm doing all the work here.
-Thank you.

474
00:30:19,096 --> 00:30:20,139
[Tony chuckles]

475
00:30:27,897 --> 00:30:29,523
<i>♪ And I know </i>♪

476
00:30:29,565 --> 00:30:31,609
<i>♪ I'm the one </i>♪

477
00:30:31,650 --> 00:30:35,321
<i>♪ You really love... </i>♪

478
00:30:37,656 --> 00:30:40,284
[new song begins]
<i>♪ Your ruby lips </i>♪

479
00:30:41,952 --> 00:30:46,082
<i>♪ Your lovely eyes </i>♪

480
00:30:47,708 --> 00:30:50,336
<i>♪ Made my life romantic </i>♪

481
00:30:50,377 --> 00:30:53,214
<i>♪ When you took advantage of me... </i>♪

482
00:30:53,255 --> 00:30:54,632
[in Russian]

483
00:31:07,812 --> 00:31:09,230
What are you looking at?

484
00:31:11,148 --> 00:31:12,650
You speak German, huh?

485
00:31:12,691 --> 00:31:14,527
That was Russian.

486
00:31:14,568 --> 00:31:16,654
Yeah, I was stationed in Germany
in the Army.

487
00:31:17,196 --> 00:31:19,990
I could pick up a little bit
of what you were saying there.

488
00:31:20,032 --> 00:31:23,577
Watch out for them Krauts.
They're all sneaks.

489
00:31:23,619 --> 00:31:26,080
Kennedy should've bombed them
when he had the chance.

490
00:31:26,122 --> 00:31:28,207
Plus, now them Cuban bastards.

491
00:31:29,875 --> 00:31:32,169
Ain't they supposed to be following us?

492
00:31:33,129 --> 00:31:36,090
They have the itinerary.
As long as they get to the show on time,

493
00:31:36,132 --> 00:31:38,384
I'm not worried about it
and neither should you.

494
00:31:39,343 --> 00:31:40,886
I ain't worried about nothing.

495
00:31:42,221 --> 00:31:44,974
In fact, when you see me worried,
you'll know.

496
00:31:45,015 --> 00:31:47,726
-Tony, how about some quiet time?
-You'll know if I'm worried.

497
00:31:48,561 --> 00:31:50,521
-Hmm?
-Sure.

498
00:31:50,563 --> 00:31:53,149
<i>♪ Your ruby lips... </i>♪

499
00:31:53,190 --> 00:31:55,776
[chuckles] It's amazing you said that.

500
00:31:56,569 --> 00:31:58,696
"How about some quiet time?"

501
00:31:58,737 --> 00:32:00,781
Dolores, my wife,
used to say that all the time.

502
00:32:00,823 --> 00:32:02,658
Well, not all the time, but you know.

503
00:32:02,700 --> 00:32:04,702
She says it when I come home
from work sometimes.

504
00:32:04,744 --> 00:32:06,287
She's been with the kids all day,

505
00:32:06,328 --> 00:32:08,998
and she'll say:
"Tony, how about some quiet time?"

506
00:32:09,039 --> 00:32:11,959
Exactly like how you said it.
I mean, it's amazing.

507
00:32:12,001 --> 00:32:13,919
[chatter]

508
00:32:19,216 --> 00:32:20,217
How is that?

509
00:32:22,636 --> 00:32:23,679
Salty.

510
00:32:26,640 --> 00:32:28,809
Have you ever considered
becoming a food critic?

511
00:32:31,812 --> 00:32:35,357
No. Not really. Why? Is there money in it?

512
00:32:35,399 --> 00:32:39,820
I'm just saying you have a marvelous way
with words when describing food.

513
00:32:40,946 --> 00:32:41,989
"Salty."

514
00:32:43,157 --> 00:32:45,201
So vivid one can almost taste it.

515
00:32:46,786 --> 00:32:49,830
Hey, I'm just saying it's salty.
And salt's cheating.

516
00:32:49,872 --> 00:32:53,459
Any cook can make things salty.
To make it taste good without the salt,

517
00:32:53,501 --> 00:32:55,795
with just the other flavors,
that's the trick.

518
00:32:55,836 --> 00:32:58,464
-You take the basic ingredients--
-We should really get going soon

519
00:32:58,506 --> 00:33:00,633
if we expect
to get to Pittsburgh by dinner.

520
00:33:01,258 --> 00:33:05,179
Hmm. Hey, when I was in the Army,
I knew a guy from Pittsburgh.

521
00:33:06,138 --> 00:33:08,390
Except he called it "Titsburgh".

522
00:33:08,432 --> 00:33:10,976
Cos he said all the women there
had huge tits.

523
00:33:12,937 --> 00:33:16,273
That's absurd. Why would women
in Pittsburgh have larger breasts

524
00:33:16,315 --> 00:33:18,484
than, say, women in New York?

525
00:33:18,526 --> 00:33:20,778
Guess we'll find out, huh? [chuckles]

526
00:33:21,946 --> 00:33:24,949
Hey, you know, when you first hired me,

527
00:33:24,990 --> 00:33:27,201
my wife went out
and bought one of your records.

528
00:33:27,243 --> 00:33:28,869
The one about the orphans.

529
00:33:29,662 --> 00:33:32,206
-Orphans?
-Yeah.

530
00:33:33,082 --> 00:33:35,251
Cover had a bunch of kids
sitting around a campfire.

531
00:33:36,419 --> 00:33:37,795
Orpheus.

532
00:33:39,255 --> 00:33:40,214
Yeah.

533
00:33:40,256 --> 00:33:42,925
<i>Orpheus In The Underworld.</i>
It's based on a French opera.

534
00:33:43,759 --> 00:33:48,180
And those weren't children on the cover.
Those were demons in the bowels of hell.

535
00:33:49,306 --> 00:33:52,184
No shit. Must have been naughty kids.

536
00:33:54,728 --> 00:33:58,566
["What'Cha Gonna Do" by Bill Massey]

537
00:34:05,448 --> 00:34:07,283
[Tony sighs]

538
00:34:07,324 --> 00:34:10,619
-What are-- What are you doing?
-Gotta take a leak, Doc.

539
00:34:11,787 --> 00:34:13,289
Here? Now?

540
00:34:13,330 --> 00:34:15,624
You want me to piss my pants?

541
00:34:15,666 --> 00:34:18,377
[song continues]

542
00:34:33,934 --> 00:34:36,520
<i>♪ What'cha gonna do? </i>♪

543
00:34:36,562 --> 00:34:38,647
[song fades out]

544
00:34:43,486 --> 00:34:46,071
[chatter and laughter outside]

545
00:34:50,451 --> 00:34:53,870
-[horn honks in distance]
-[woman laughing]

546
00:34:53,913 --> 00:34:55,955
[chatter continues]

547
00:34:59,919 --> 00:35:03,089
[laughing]

548
00:35:07,301 --> 00:35:09,929
[soft ambient music]

549
00:35:29,073 --> 00:35:31,492
[soft ambient music fades out]

550
00:35:33,994 --> 00:35:35,621
-Oh, hey, Doc.
-Good afternoon.

551
00:35:35,663 --> 00:35:37,248
[Tony clears throat]

552
00:35:37,289 --> 00:35:39,792
Take this for any incidentals we may need.

553
00:35:40,501 --> 00:35:42,920
If you wanna buy something,
you don't have to ask.

554
00:35:42,962 --> 00:35:46,507
Just keep the receipts, please.
When it runs low, let me know.

555
00:35:46,549 --> 00:35:49,135
-Oh. Thanks.
-One more thing.

556
00:35:51,053 --> 00:35:53,013
We'll be attending...

557
00:35:53,055 --> 00:35:56,559
many events before and after the concerts,
interacting with some of the wealthiest

558
00:35:56,600 --> 00:35:58,894
and most highly-educated people
in the country.

559
00:35:59,770 --> 00:36:02,231
It is my feeling that your diction,

560
00:36:02,273 --> 00:36:04,608
however charming it may be
in the tristate area,

561
00:36:04,650 --> 00:36:07,278
could use some... finessing.

562
00:36:07,319 --> 00:36:10,114
You mean diction... like in what way?

563
00:36:11,657 --> 00:36:13,617
Like in the only way
the word is ever used.

564
00:36:14,994 --> 00:36:15,911
Okay.

565
00:36:15,953 --> 00:36:18,748
Your intonation, inflection,
your choice of words.

566
00:36:19,999 --> 00:36:21,333
Hey, I got my own problems.

567
00:36:21,375 --> 00:36:23,878
Now I gotta worry about
what people think about the way I talk?

568
00:36:23,919 --> 00:36:26,630
There are simple techniques
I can teach you that are effective.

569
00:36:26,672 --> 00:36:29,091
-I can help you.
-I don't need no goddamn help.

570
00:36:29,133 --> 00:36:31,802
People don't like the way I talk,
they can go take a shit.

571
00:36:32,887 --> 00:36:34,638
The profanity is another issue.

572
00:36:34,680 --> 00:36:37,224
[swears in Italian]
Why are you breaking my balls?

573
00:36:37,266 --> 00:36:41,312
Because you can do better, Mr Vallelonga.
Which brings me to one more point.

574
00:36:41,854 --> 00:36:45,733
As the guest of honor, I'll be introduced
when entering these intimate events.

575
00:36:45,775 --> 00:36:49,445
You will be introduced as well.
In my humble opinion...

576
00:36:50,446 --> 00:36:52,907
"Vallelonga" may be difficult
to pronounce.

577
00:36:52,948 --> 00:36:56,452
So I was thinking...
"Valle" would be more appropriate.

578
00:36:56,494 --> 00:36:59,538
-[chuckles]
-Tony Valle. Short and sweet.

579
00:37:00,414 --> 00:37:01,916
Eh... Nah.

580
00:37:02,792 --> 00:37:05,461
They got a problem with Vallelonga,
they can call me Tony Lip.

581
00:37:05,503 --> 00:37:09,632
These are genteel people.
"Tony the Lip" may be a little...

582
00:37:10,883 --> 00:37:14,220
-worldly for them.
-Well, then it's Tony Vallelonga.

583
00:37:14,845 --> 00:37:17,932
All these high-class people,
so much smarter than me,

584
00:37:17,973 --> 00:37:20,351
with their intelligence
and speaking abilities,

585
00:37:20,392 --> 00:37:22,478
you tell me they can't pronounce my name?

586
00:37:22,520 --> 00:37:25,523
They don't like it, they can shove it
up their ass, I'll just wait outside.

587
00:37:27,399 --> 00:37:28,901
A sound compromise.

588
00:37:29,443 --> 00:37:32,196
[piano playing mid-tempo jazz intro]

589
00:37:36,325 --> 00:37:38,828
[jazz band joins in]

590
00:37:38,869 --> 00:37:41,330
[chatter and laughter]

591
00:37:45,334 --> 00:37:48,254
Ladies and gentlemen,
tonight we are privileged

592
00:37:48,295 --> 00:37:51,048
to present a great American artist.

593
00:37:55,594 --> 00:37:58,806
At age 18, at Arthur Fiedler's invitation,

594
00:37:58,848 --> 00:38:02,852
our guest made his concert debut
with the Boston Pops.

595
00:38:02,893 --> 00:38:08,274
He holds Doctorates in Psychology,
in Music, and in the Liturgical Arts.

596
00:38:08,315 --> 00:38:12,361
And he has performed at the White House
twice in the past 14 months.

597
00:38:12,403 --> 00:38:14,864
He is a true virtuoso.

598
00:38:22,413 --> 00:38:25,040
...unique artist.
So, ladies and gentlemen,

599
00:38:25,082 --> 00:38:28,127
please welcome the Don Shirley Trio.

600
00:38:28,169 --> 00:38:30,504
[applause]

601
00:38:38,637 --> 00:38:41,015
[dramatic intro in a minor key]

602
00:38:58,532 --> 00:39:01,035
[jazzy, syncopated, fugue-like melody]

603
00:39:03,287 --> 00:39:05,664
[cello joins in]

604
00:39:39,907 --> 00:39:41,534
[chuckles]

605
00:40:01,345 --> 00:40:03,472
-[lively chatter]
-A new pair of shoes!

606
00:40:03,514 --> 00:40:05,266
[excited shouts]

607
00:40:05,307 --> 00:40:08,185
-Hard ten! Lady's friend.
-He keeps on winning!

608
00:40:08,227 --> 00:40:10,104
It's your dice.
I'm just having a lucky night.

609
00:40:10,146 --> 00:40:12,273
-You cheating, brother!
-[Dr Shirley] Tony.

610
00:40:12,314 --> 00:40:15,234
-Get him again. Get him again.
-Boss man's calling.

611
00:40:15,276 --> 00:40:18,070
He ain't my boss.
I work for the record company.

612
00:40:18,112 --> 00:40:20,573
-Yeah, I work for the record company, too!
-Hey, hey, hey!

613
00:40:20,614 --> 00:40:23,159
Hey, come on, man. Give us a chance
to win back our loot, huh?

614
00:40:23,200 --> 00:40:25,703
-I'm sorry, fellas, duty calls.
-Come on, man.

615
00:40:25,745 --> 00:40:29,248
"Duty calls"? My man,
my duty is to get my money back.

616
00:40:30,124 --> 00:40:31,709
I've been looking for you.

617
00:40:31,751 --> 00:40:34,754
Yeah, sorry.
The guys were having a little game.

618
00:40:34,795 --> 00:40:37,548
Next time you need extra money,
you just ask me.

619
00:40:37,590 --> 00:40:39,300
It's more fun winning it.

620
00:40:39,341 --> 00:40:40,968
And what if you lost?

621
00:40:41,844 --> 00:40:45,181
Grab some cards. I don't lose, Doc.
I don't lose.

622
00:40:46,474 --> 00:40:49,852
Stooping down in the gravel, pitching dice
for pocket change makes you a winner?

623
00:40:51,395 --> 00:40:54,064
What are you giving me shit for?
Everybody was doing it.

624
00:40:54,106 --> 00:40:56,525
They didn't have a choice
whether to be inside or out.

625
00:40:58,152 --> 00:40:59,069
You did.

626
00:41:02,656 --> 00:41:04,742
Now, wipe off your knees.
You have dirt on them.

627
00:41:04,784 --> 00:41:06,744
[soft ambient music]

628
00:41:13,125 --> 00:41:15,211
[birdsong]

629
00:41:15,252 --> 00:41:18,547
[music intensifies]

630
00:41:25,387 --> 00:41:30,142
[Tony] <i>Dear Dolores, how are you?
I am fine.</i>

631
00:41:30,184 --> 00:41:32,978
"I'm eating real good. Hamburgers, mostly.

632
00:41:33,687 --> 00:41:35,940
So don't worry about me not eating good.

633
00:41:36,774 --> 00:41:40,778
I saw Dr Shirley play the piano tonight.

634
00:41:40,820 --> 00:41:45,157
He don't play like a colored guy.
He plays like Liberace, but better.

635
00:41:46,325 --> 00:41:48,536
He's like a genius, I think.

636
00:41:48,577 --> 00:41:50,746
When I look at him
in the rear-view mirror,

637
00:41:50,788 --> 00:41:53,874
I can tell he's always thinking
about stuff in his head.

638
00:41:53,916 --> 00:41:56,127
I guess that's what geniuses do.

639
00:41:56,168 --> 00:41:58,629
But it don't look fun to be that smart.

640
00:41:59,672 --> 00:42:02,299
I miss you very, very much."

641
00:42:02,967 --> 00:42:05,094
["Lucille" by Little Richard]

642
00:42:07,138 --> 00:42:08,597
[music continues on radio]

643
00:42:12,059 --> 00:42:13,894
-Who is this?
-Who?

644
00:42:14,562 --> 00:42:16,063
On the radio.

645
00:42:17,231 --> 00:42:21,402
-Little Richard.
-Really? That's Little Richard?

646
00:42:21,444 --> 00:42:24,029
Yeah. Think you could play
something like that, Doc?

647
00:42:24,071 --> 00:42:25,489
<i>♪ Lucille... </i>♪

648
00:42:26,282 --> 00:42:29,076
I don't know. Sounds fairly complicated.

649
00:42:29,118 --> 00:42:30,619
Got that right.

650
00:42:32,204 --> 00:42:34,373
So where did
this "Tony the Lip" moniker come from?

651
00:42:34,415 --> 00:42:39,837
[chuckles] It's not Tony <i>the </i>Lip.
It's Tony Lip. One word.

652
00:42:39,879 --> 00:42:42,381
I got it when I was a kid,
cos my friend said

653
00:42:42,423 --> 00:42:45,968
I was the best bullshit artist
in the Bronx. [chuckles]

654
00:42:46,010 --> 00:42:48,763
-Why are you smiling?
-What do you mean?

655
00:42:49,722 --> 00:42:51,515
It doesn't bother you that your friends,

656
00:42:51,557 --> 00:42:53,768
the people closest to you
consider you a liar?

657
00:42:53,809 --> 00:42:57,188
Who said "liar"? I said "bullshit artist".

658
00:42:57,229 --> 00:43:01,233
-And what's the difference?
-Cos I don't lie. Ever.

659
00:43:01,275 --> 00:43:03,444
I'm just good at talking people into...

660
00:43:03,486 --> 00:43:05,863
you know, doing things
they don't wanna do.

661
00:43:05,905 --> 00:43:07,239
By bullshitting them.

662
00:43:07,990 --> 00:43:11,160
-And you're proud of that?
-Well, it got me this job.

663
00:43:11,202 --> 00:43:13,829
<i>♪ Lucille, please don't... </i>♪

664
00:43:13,871 --> 00:43:16,749
[Chubby Checker]
<i>♪ Baby, baby, baby, take it easy... </i>♪

665
00:43:16,791 --> 00:43:20,503
Wait a minute. You're full of shit.
You never heard of Chubby Checker?

666
00:43:20,544 --> 00:43:23,005
Of course I've heard of him.
I just never heard his music.

667
00:43:23,047 --> 00:43:25,925
-I mean...
-But I like this. This is nice.

668
00:43:27,218 --> 00:43:30,262
-He's got a silky voice, very smooth.
-Yeah, he's terrific.

669
00:43:30,304 --> 00:43:33,724
-This is what everybody's dancing to now.
-Eyes on the road, Tony.

670
00:43:35,059 --> 00:43:36,769
[Aretha Franklin] <i>♪ Baby, here I am... </i>♪

671
00:43:36,811 --> 00:43:38,395
You know this song.

672
00:43:39,063 --> 00:43:42,483
-I don't think so, no.
-How could you not know this music?

673
00:43:42,525 --> 00:43:44,110
Aretha Franklin!

674
00:43:45,194 --> 00:43:47,780
Chubby Checker, Little Richard, Sam Cooke.

675
00:43:47,822 --> 00:43:50,616
I mean, come on, Doc.
These are <i>your </i>people.

676
00:43:51,534 --> 00:43:55,454
<i>♪ And it won't be long
No, it won't be long... </i>♪

677
00:43:55,496 --> 00:43:57,581
[insects buzzing]

678
00:44:04,964 --> 00:44:06,090
Do you want anything?

679
00:44:06,132 --> 00:44:08,300
-I'm getting a pack of smokes.
-No, thank you.

680
00:44:08,843 --> 00:44:10,845
[stones crunching underfoot]

681
00:44:11,971 --> 00:44:13,222
[sighs]

682
00:44:24,024 --> 00:44:25,526
[sighs]

683
00:44:33,576 --> 00:44:35,453
-[bells jingling]
-[sighs]

684
00:44:36,871 --> 00:44:40,040
[Oleg speaking softly] ...grabbed the rock
and put it in his pocket.

685
00:44:40,082 --> 00:44:41,208
Thank you, Oleg.

686
00:44:42,168 --> 00:44:44,462
Nice turtleneck. Way to mix it up.

687
00:44:48,007 --> 00:44:49,550
Got you an apple, Doc.

688
00:44:49,592 --> 00:44:51,927
-[engine starts]
-[Tony grunts]

689
00:44:55,514 --> 00:44:57,892
Before we pull out, Tony,
we need to have a talk.

690
00:45:00,227 --> 00:45:02,480
-Yeah?
-Oleg told me what you did.

691
00:45:03,230 --> 00:45:06,400
-What'd I do?
-You stole a jade stone from the store.

692
00:45:06,442 --> 00:45:08,652
-No, I didn't.
-He watched you do it.

693
00:45:08,694 --> 00:45:10,446
I didn't steal no stone!

694
00:45:10,488 --> 00:45:12,364
You picked it up
and put it in your pocket.

695
00:45:12,406 --> 00:45:15,493
I picked up a rock off of the ground.
I didn't steal from a box.

696
00:45:15,534 --> 00:45:17,369
Why would you pick up
a rock off the ground?

697
00:45:17,411 --> 00:45:18,621
I don't know.

698
00:45:20,081 --> 00:45:22,750
Cos it ain't stealing.
It's just a regular rock.

699
00:45:22,792 --> 00:45:24,376
And why would you want a regular rock?

700
00:45:25,544 --> 00:45:28,881
-To have. For luck, maybe.
-A lucky rock.

701
00:45:28,923 --> 00:45:30,758
-Yeah.
-Let me see it.

702
00:45:36,222 --> 00:45:37,515
[Tony sighs]

703
00:45:42,728 --> 00:45:43,896
Mm-mm.

704
00:45:45,356 --> 00:45:47,066
Take it back and pay for it.

705
00:45:48,359 --> 00:45:51,112
[swears in Italian]
I told you that Kraut was a snake.

706
00:45:51,153 --> 00:45:54,115
Rats me out
for something I didn't even do!

707
00:45:54,156 --> 00:45:56,951
-Pay for the stone, you'll feel better.
-I feel fine.

708
00:45:56,992 --> 00:45:59,995
And I ain't paying
for no regular rock I found in the dirt.

709
00:46:01,205 --> 00:46:03,249
Do not drive, Mr Vallelonga.

710
00:46:04,708 --> 00:46:05,960
[Tony sighs]

711
00:46:07,128 --> 00:46:08,546
Put it back.

712
00:46:14,718 --> 00:46:17,680
[piano playing softly]

713
00:46:30,067 --> 00:46:32,736
[starts engine]

714
00:46:32,778 --> 00:46:34,280
-Feel better?
-No.

715
00:46:35,531 --> 00:46:38,242
If you'd like, Tony,
I'd happily buy you the stone.

716
00:46:38,284 --> 00:46:41,162
Don't bother.
You took all the fun out of it.

717
00:46:43,539 --> 00:46:45,499
[piano playing fades out]

718
00:46:50,337 --> 00:46:52,381
[cello playing classical music]

719
00:47:18,282 --> 00:47:19,867
Excuse me. Sir.

720
00:47:21,327 --> 00:47:23,329
-I'm with the band.
-You're all set up.

721
00:47:23,370 --> 00:47:25,581
This isn't the piano, right?

722
00:47:25,623 --> 00:47:28,334
-That's it.
-It ain't a Steinway.

723
00:47:29,251 --> 00:47:30,252
So what?

724
00:47:30,294 --> 00:47:33,214
Dr Shirley only plays
on Steinway grand pianos.

725
00:47:33,255 --> 00:47:34,965
It's in his written contract.

726
00:47:35,007 --> 00:47:36,425
Who's Dr Shirley?

727
00:47:36,467 --> 00:47:40,638
Dr Shirley. The Don Shirley Trio.
They're playing tonight.

728
00:47:40,679 --> 00:47:44,892
-Does it really matter?
-Yeah, it does. It's in his contract.

729
00:47:46,811 --> 00:47:50,314
Come on, man. Man, these coons can play
on anything you put in front of them.

730
00:47:54,610 --> 00:47:56,237
But it's a piece of shit.

731
00:47:56,278 --> 00:47:59,031
-And there's garbage in there.
-So take it out.

732
00:48:00,324 --> 00:48:01,492
What'd you say?

733
00:48:03,411 --> 00:48:04,662
You heard me.

734
00:48:07,623 --> 00:48:12,378
Hey. You got two, three hours.
Just get a clean Steinway in here.

735
00:48:12,420 --> 00:48:15,131
-Oh, there ain't a Steinway on campus.
-Not my problem.

736
00:48:15,172 --> 00:48:18,217
[scoffs] I bet there's not two Steinways
in the whole state of Indiana.

737
00:48:18,259 --> 00:48:20,594
I guess you'd better move your ass, then.

738
00:48:20,636 --> 00:48:23,305
Who you think you're talking to,
greaseball? [grunts]

739
00:48:25,307 --> 00:48:27,351
[whimpers]

740
00:48:27,393 --> 00:48:30,938
[plays "Happy Talk" by Richard Rodgers
and Oscar Hammerstein II]

741
00:48:52,626 --> 00:48:57,882
[Tony] <i>Dear Dolores, this morning
I had steak and eggs. For breakfast.</i>

742
00:48:57,923 --> 00:49:01,135
<i>The band has been playing
at very ritzy joints.</i>

743
00:49:01,927 --> 00:49:04,930
<i>Dr Shirley and I
are getting along pretty good.</i>

744
00:49:04,972 --> 00:49:08,601
<i>But sometimes I think he gets sad
and that's why he drinks too much.</i>

745
00:49:09,477 --> 00:49:12,772
<i>I never knew
how very beautiful this country was.</i>

746
00:49:12,813 --> 00:49:15,191
<i>Now that I'm seeing it, I know.</i>

747
00:49:15,232 --> 00:49:17,651
<i>You won't believe
how beautiful nature is.</i>

748
00:49:17,693 --> 00:49:19,695
<i>It is as beautiful as they say.</i>

749
00:49:20,446 --> 00:49:24,366
<i>And the traffic out here in the country
is nothing, which is fine by me.</i>

750
00:49:25,034 --> 00:49:27,661
<i>Right now I'm eating
spaghetti and meatballs, in a diner,</i>

751
00:49:27,703 --> 00:49:30,164
<i>that tastes like
ketchup on Chinese noodles.</i>

752
00:49:31,040 --> 00:49:32,833
<i>We are heading down south now.</i>

753
00:49:32,875 --> 00:49:35,836
<i>I will write you another letter
when we get down south.</i>

754
00:49:35,878 --> 00:49:40,508
<i>I love you. Your husband, Tony.
PS. Kiss the kids for me.</i>

755
00:49:40,549 --> 00:49:42,760
-[music ends]
-[applause]

756
00:49:43,928 --> 00:49:47,848
["Ba-da" by Roy 'Boogie Boy' Perkins]

757
00:49:49,850 --> 00:49:52,520
-Got any family, Doc?
-Not really.

758
00:49:52,561 --> 00:49:55,314
Not really? Either you do or you don't.

759
00:49:56,941 --> 00:50:00,528
-It's a long story, Tony.
-What, we're in a hurry now?

760
00:50:02,071 --> 00:50:04,156
-[turns down music]
-Let's hear it.

761
00:50:05,282 --> 00:50:07,326
I have a brother somewhere.

762
00:50:08,327 --> 00:50:10,162
We used to get together once in a while,

763
00:50:10,204 --> 00:50:12,665
but it got more and more difficult
to stay in touch.

764
00:50:13,541 --> 00:50:15,584
Curse of being a musician, I guess.

765
00:50:16,794 --> 00:50:20,548
Always on the road.
Like a carnival worker.

766
00:50:20,589 --> 00:50:22,675
-Hmm.
-Or a criminal.

767
00:50:23,592 --> 00:50:26,053
Took quite the toll
on my marriage as well.

768
00:50:26,095 --> 00:50:27,972
-<i>You</i>'re married?
-Was.

769
00:50:28,013 --> 00:50:29,515
June.

770
00:50:30,641 --> 00:50:32,268
Good person.

771
00:50:32,309 --> 00:50:35,771
Terrible grammar, but a kind soul.
You'd quite like her.

772
00:50:35,813 --> 00:50:39,358
June. Like, uh, like Lassie's mom.

773
00:50:41,569 --> 00:50:45,823
Unfortunately, I couldn't do a husband act
and a concert pianist act.

774
00:50:47,032 --> 00:50:49,493
Couldn't seem to manage both worlds.

775
00:50:51,495 --> 00:50:53,664
[Tony] "Kentucky Fried Chicken."

776
00:50:53,706 --> 00:50:56,917
In Kentucky!
When's that ever gonna happen?

777
00:50:57,418 --> 00:51:01,130
["Cookin'" by Al Casey Combo]

778
00:51:06,635 --> 00:51:09,555
[chuckles] All right!

779
00:51:11,432 --> 00:51:14,435
-Hey, you want some?
-I'm fine. Thank you, Tony.

780
00:51:14,477 --> 00:51:15,519
All right.

781
00:51:16,729 --> 00:51:18,230
Mmm.

782
00:51:18,272 --> 00:51:22,193
I think this is the best
Kentucky Fried Chicken I ever had.

783
00:51:23,194 --> 00:51:25,029
Probably cos it's fresher
down here, right?

784
00:51:25,070 --> 00:51:27,448
I don't think I've ever met anyone
with your appetite.

785
00:51:27,490 --> 00:51:30,034
No. I got the bucket,
so you could have some.

786
00:51:30,075 --> 00:51:34,538
-I've never had fried chicken in my life.
-Who you bullshitting?

787
00:51:35,122 --> 00:51:38,501
You people love the fried chicken,
the grits and the collard greens.

788
00:51:39,168 --> 00:51:40,211
I love it, too.

789
00:51:40,252 --> 00:51:43,464
Negro cooks used to make it all the time
when I was in the Army.

790
00:51:43,506 --> 00:51:46,050
You have
a very narrow assessment of me, Tony.

791
00:51:46,092 --> 00:51:48,511
Yeah, right? I'm good.

792
00:51:48,552 --> 00:51:52,223
No. No, you're not good.
You're bad. I'm saying,

793
00:51:52,264 --> 00:51:55,935
just because other Negroes enjoy certain
types of music, it doesn't mean I have to.

794
00:51:55,976 --> 00:52:00,147
-Nor do we all eat the same kind of food.
-Whoa! Wait a minute.

795
00:52:00,189 --> 00:52:03,484
If you said all guineas like pizza,
and spaghetti and meatballs,

796
00:52:03,526 --> 00:52:06,195
-I'm not gonna get insulted.
-You're missing the point.

797
00:52:06,237 --> 00:52:09,323
-For you to assume that every Negro--
-Hey, you want some or not?

798
00:52:09,365 --> 00:52:11,700
-No.
-Here. Come on.

799
00:52:11,742 --> 00:52:13,452
-Tell me that don't smell good.
-It...

800
00:52:13,494 --> 00:52:15,413
-Huh?
-It smells okay.

801
00:52:15,454 --> 00:52:18,457
I prefer not to get grease on my blanket.

802
00:52:18,499 --> 00:52:21,293
"Ooh, I'm gonna get grease on my blankey!"

803
00:52:21,335 --> 00:52:24,255
Have a piece. It ain't gonna kill you.
Come on, take it, eat it.

804
00:52:24,296 --> 00:52:26,674
-No.
-Take it. I'm throwing it in the back.

805
00:52:26,715 --> 00:52:29,009
-You-- Don't you dare.
-Then you better take it.

806
00:52:29,051 --> 00:52:31,470
How? Do you have plates or utensils?

807
00:52:31,512 --> 00:52:34,265
Eat it with your hands,
that's how you're supposed to.

808
00:52:34,306 --> 00:52:36,225
-I can't do that.
-Eat it. Come on. Take it.

809
00:52:36,267 --> 00:52:37,977
I gotta drive. Ten and two on the wheel.

810
00:52:38,018 --> 00:52:40,646
-Tony... [groans]
-Come on! Take it! Come on.

811
00:52:41,230 --> 00:52:43,732
There you go. Huh?

812
00:52:44,984 --> 00:52:46,277
I... I can't do this, Tony.

813
00:52:46,318 --> 00:52:48,320
Eat the goddamn thing!

814
00:52:49,238 --> 00:52:50,322
Jesus.

815
00:52:52,908 --> 00:52:54,952
[rock and roll on radio]

816
00:53:00,541 --> 00:53:03,127
-What, no good?
-Mm.

817
00:53:03,169 --> 00:53:06,714
["Go To the Mardi Gras"
by Professor Longhair]

818
00:53:07,882 --> 00:53:09,175
It just seems...

819
00:53:10,885 --> 00:53:12,928
so un-- unsanitary.

820
00:53:12,970 --> 00:53:14,430
Who gives a shit?

821
00:53:15,055 --> 00:53:16,932
Just relax and enjoy it.

822
00:53:17,683 --> 00:53:19,477
You know, my father used to say...

823
00:53:20,352 --> 00:53:23,022
"Whatever you do, do it 100%.

824
00:53:23,063 --> 00:53:25,900
When you work, work.
When you laugh, laugh.

825
00:53:25,941 --> 00:53:28,778
When you eat,
eat like it's your last meal."

826
00:53:29,695 --> 00:53:33,699
You want another piece? Here.
Have a breast. Delicious.

827
00:53:35,242 --> 00:53:38,954
-Take it. Here you go.
-What do we do about the bones?

828
00:53:41,999 --> 00:53:43,000
We do this.

829
00:53:45,211 --> 00:53:46,670
This is what we do.

830
00:53:46,712 --> 00:53:50,716
<i>♪ If you go to New Orleans
You ought to go see the Mardi Gras... </i>♪

831
00:53:54,887 --> 00:53:56,931
-There you go.
-[both laugh]

832
00:53:56,972 --> 00:53:59,391
<i>♪ You ought to go see the Mardi Gras </i>♪

833
00:54:02,228 --> 00:54:04,980
<i>♪ When you see the Mardi Gras... </i>♪

834
00:54:07,024 --> 00:54:09,985
What's the big deal, Doc?
The squirrels would've eaten it anyway.

835
00:54:10,027 --> 00:54:12,154
-Pick it up, Tony.
-Nature takes care of the Earth.

836
00:54:12,196 --> 00:54:13,697
-Pick it up.
-Aw, geez.

837
00:54:13,739 --> 00:54:15,908
<i>♪ If you wanna go to New Orleans... </i>♪

838
00:54:21,330 --> 00:54:23,666
[chatter]

839
00:54:26,001 --> 00:54:27,545
[Tony grunts]

840
00:54:27,586 --> 00:54:30,423
-[lively chatter]
-[door slams]

841
00:54:34,718 --> 00:54:36,762
[train horn blares in distance]

842
00:54:36,804 --> 00:54:38,264
[cat meows]

843
00:54:44,353 --> 00:54:45,604
[cat meows]

844
00:54:48,149 --> 00:54:49,442
This can't be right.

845
00:54:52,319 --> 00:54:56,115
It says right here:
"Cozy as your own home."

846
00:54:57,783 --> 00:55:00,953
-Place looks like my ass.
-This is the place.

847
00:55:04,832 --> 00:55:06,083
[Tony sighs heavily]

848
00:55:07,835 --> 00:55:09,336
The square one, please.

849
00:55:10,463 --> 00:55:12,798
-Just this one?
-Thank you.

850
00:55:16,469 --> 00:55:17,803
Hey, uh...

851
00:55:18,471 --> 00:55:21,974
if you need anything, I'll be
right up the street at the Easton Inn.

852
00:55:22,808 --> 00:55:24,018
Thank you, Tony.

853
00:55:24,059 --> 00:55:26,395
[chatter, music playing over radio]

854
00:55:26,437 --> 00:55:27,688
[dog barking]

855
00:55:28,481 --> 00:55:30,649
-Hey, Floyd, we ready.
-I told you.

856
00:55:30,691 --> 00:55:34,028
-I can't play, my shoulder.
-You and that damn shoulder.

857
00:55:36,030 --> 00:55:37,990
Hey! Hey, fancy-pants!

858
00:55:38,032 --> 00:55:41,076
-You wanna play?
-I beg your pardon?

859
00:55:41,118 --> 00:55:42,870
Come on, brother, we short a man.

860
00:55:44,413 --> 00:55:45,915
Oh, I... I'd rather not.

861
00:55:46,749 --> 00:55:48,626
What, you too high and mighty?

862
00:55:48,667 --> 00:55:51,128
[other man]
No, no, let him alone, let him alone.

863
00:55:51,170 --> 00:55:53,881
He just afraid of getting
that butler uniform dusty.

864
00:55:53,923 --> 00:55:57,384
Mm. I'm just, um...

865
00:55:58,844 --> 00:56:00,471
I'm on my way to meet a friend.

866
00:56:01,597 --> 00:56:03,307
Yeah, well, thanks for nothing.

867
00:56:05,351 --> 00:56:07,603
-[men laughing]
-Floyd, come on, man!

868
00:56:07,645 --> 00:56:10,106
Shut your ass up, man, and leave me alone!

869
00:56:13,150 --> 00:56:15,277
[soft ambient music]

870
00:56:20,116 --> 00:56:21,408
[groans]

871
00:56:25,413 --> 00:56:28,416
[sighs, sniffs]

872
00:56:39,552 --> 00:56:40,719
Mm.

873
00:56:42,138 --> 00:56:43,222
Yeah.

874
00:56:44,640 --> 00:56:47,560
"For vacation without aggravation."

875
00:56:50,062 --> 00:56:51,272
Hmm.

876
00:56:57,236 --> 00:57:00,573
"Delightful dinners
for particular people."

877
00:57:00,614 --> 00:57:02,908
[urgent knocking on door]

878
00:57:02,950 --> 00:57:04,535
-Yeah?
-Get up! It's George!

879
00:57:04,577 --> 00:57:06,078
[George panting] Get up.

880
00:57:07,037 --> 00:57:09,081
Tony, come on. Hurry up.

881
00:57:10,875 --> 00:57:12,585
Dr Shirley's in trouble.

882
00:57:12,626 --> 00:57:14,670
I went out for a drink,
I walk into this bar,

883
00:57:14,712 --> 00:57:16,839
and Dr Shirley's in there
getting bounced around.

884
00:57:16,881 --> 00:57:19,175
I didn't wanna leave him,
but I didn't know what to do.

885
00:57:19,216 --> 00:57:20,676
Who let him out of his cage?

886
00:57:20,718 --> 00:57:23,888
And they put that little tie on him, too.
Why you all dressed up?

887
00:57:23,929 --> 00:57:25,931
-[grunting and laughter]
-[door opens]

888
00:57:25,973 --> 00:57:27,808
Get your hands off him.

889
00:57:30,644 --> 00:57:33,230
What in the good goddamn
we got here, fellas?

890
00:57:33,272 --> 00:57:36,650
Hand him over,
we walk out, won't be a problem.

891
00:57:36,692 --> 00:57:38,944
I just wanted a drink, Tony.

892
00:57:38,986 --> 00:57:41,030
Hey, I told you we'll leave.

893
00:57:41,071 --> 00:57:43,866
-Not a big deal. Come on.
-He ain't going nowhere.

894
00:57:43,908 --> 00:57:45,910
We need a Brillo Pad
to wash these dishes with.

895
00:57:45,951 --> 00:57:47,661
[Tony] Listen, assholes.

896
00:57:47,703 --> 00:57:50,122
Do yourselves a favor and let him go.

897
00:57:50,956 --> 00:57:52,124
Now!

898
00:57:54,210 --> 00:57:55,503
Say it nice.

899
00:57:56,837 --> 00:57:58,339
I just said it nice.

900
00:57:59,048 --> 00:58:02,134
This boy is gonna get
what he's got coming to him.

901
00:58:03,094 --> 00:58:04,261
[click]

902
00:58:04,303 --> 00:58:07,681
And you... you ain't got no say.

903
00:58:10,684 --> 00:58:12,978
Maybe. But whatever happens here,

904
00:58:13,562 --> 00:58:16,732
I'm gonna put a bullet
right in the middle of your thick skull.

905
00:58:18,192 --> 00:58:21,570
He ain't got no gun, Ray.
He's full of shit!

906
00:58:22,947 --> 00:58:24,573
What if he ain't?

907
00:58:28,411 --> 00:58:29,829
Well, I sure ain't.

908
00:58:31,122 --> 00:58:34,166
And I ain't about to let this
come to pass in my place.

909
00:58:37,420 --> 00:58:39,713
Let the spook go. Let him go.

910
00:58:40,881 --> 00:58:41,882
Come on.

911
00:58:43,551 --> 00:58:44,760
Get him out of here.

912
00:58:45,511 --> 00:58:49,557
[bartender] I want these Yankees
off of my property. Go on.

913
00:58:49,598 --> 00:58:51,183
Go on, George. Go. Go.

914
00:58:51,225 --> 00:58:52,601
[George] I got you, Doc.

915
00:58:55,312 --> 00:58:56,355
[bartender] Go on.

916
00:59:03,529 --> 00:59:05,614
-You out of your mind?
-I'm sorry.

917
00:59:05,656 --> 00:59:08,033
I didn't mean to put you in that position.

918
00:59:09,076 --> 00:59:10,619
Wait, wait, wait.

919
00:59:10,661 --> 00:59:13,164
-Are you gonna throw up again?
-[groans]

920
00:59:14,999 --> 00:59:16,375
I'm okay.

921
00:59:16,417 --> 00:59:18,919
Honest to God, Doc,
I don't understand you.

922
00:59:18,961 --> 00:59:21,422
You could have drunk here.
You got a whole bottle.

923
00:59:21,464 --> 00:59:23,883
-I just needed some air.
-Air?

924
00:59:23,924 --> 00:59:25,760
Do you know where you are?

925
00:59:27,136 --> 00:59:29,096
Does geography really matter?

926
00:59:30,139 --> 00:59:31,056
What?

927
00:59:31,849 --> 00:59:35,186
If I was in a bar
in your neighborhood, would...

928
00:59:36,353 --> 00:59:38,272
the conversation be any different?

929
00:59:38,314 --> 00:59:40,858
[soft ambient music]

930
00:59:40,900 --> 00:59:44,320
From now on, you don't go
nowhere without me. Nowhere!

931
00:59:46,113 --> 00:59:47,782
-Got it?
-I understand.

932
00:59:49,867 --> 00:59:51,786
-Where's your room?
-Tony...

933
00:59:53,370 --> 00:59:54,246
What?

934
00:59:55,539 --> 00:59:57,583
Do you really have a gun?

935
00:59:57,625 --> 00:59:59,085
Course not.

936
01:00:00,336 --> 01:00:02,797
Doc, where's your goddamn room?

937
01:00:06,926 --> 01:00:08,969
-Come on. Over there?
-There it is.

938
01:00:10,054 --> 01:00:13,015
You gotta get to bed, Doc, you got
a big show tomorrow night. Come on.

939
01:00:13,682 --> 01:00:15,726
[up-tempo jazz]

940
01:00:28,072 --> 01:00:31,367
-[music ends]
-[cheering and applause]

941
01:00:33,411 --> 01:00:34,745
[Dr Shirley] Thank you.

942
01:00:35,371 --> 01:00:38,999
Louisville,
thank you for your warm hospitality.

943
01:00:39,041 --> 01:00:40,668
-[applause]
-[man] Bravo!

944
01:00:40,709 --> 01:00:42,753
[applause continues]

945
01:00:44,088 --> 01:00:46,298
Thank you. Thank you.

946
01:00:48,759 --> 01:00:50,261
["Why Oh Why" by Little Alice]

947
01:00:50,302 --> 01:00:54,348
<i>♪ Why, oh, why has my baby... </i>♪

948
01:00:54,390 --> 01:00:56,725
-Don't be lazy, Tony. Enunciate.
-I am!

949
01:00:56,767 --> 01:01:00,729
[Dr Shirley] Betty bought a bit of better
butter to make the bitter butter better.

950
01:01:00,771 --> 01:01:03,649
[Tony] B-- Betty bought butta-er.

951
01:01:03,691 --> 01:01:06,527
Butta-- Who says that? Butta-<i>er.</i>

952
01:01:06,569 --> 01:01:09,530
You have to start somewhere, Tony.
A singer does vocal exercises.

953
01:01:09,572 --> 01:01:11,407
An athlete warms up before they rehearse.

954
01:01:11,449 --> 01:01:13,159
[Tony]
Athletes practice. They don't rehearse.

955
01:01:13,200 --> 01:01:15,077
[clanking, steam hissing]

956
01:01:15,119 --> 01:01:17,037
Ah, shit.

957
01:01:23,210 --> 01:01:25,296
-[steam hissing]
-[grunts]

958
01:02:00,706 --> 01:02:04,752
[soft ambient music]

959
01:02:16,097 --> 01:02:17,640
[car boot slams shut]

960
01:02:34,448 --> 01:02:35,658
[Tony grunts]

961
01:02:37,910 --> 01:02:41,831
[music intensifies]

962
01:02:42,373 --> 01:02:47,545
[man] Ladies and gentlemen,
a very special guest from the far north,

963
01:02:47,586 --> 01:02:50,339
-Don Shirley.
-[applause]

964
01:02:53,467 --> 01:02:56,804
Accompanying Mr Shirley,
the members of his trio,

965
01:02:56,846 --> 01:03:00,433
Oleg Malacovich, George Dyer,

966
01:03:00,474 --> 01:03:05,646
and his associate Tony Valle--
Valle-- Vallelong-longia.

967
01:03:05,688 --> 01:03:06,897
[applause]

968
01:03:11,485 --> 01:03:13,237
Oh, this is my lovely wife, Margaret.

969
01:03:13,279 --> 01:03:14,864
If you gentlemen don't mind,

970
01:03:14,905 --> 01:03:17,616
we're gonna steal Donnie away
for some introductions.

971
01:03:19,910 --> 01:03:22,288
I'd like you all to meet Don Shirley.

972
01:03:22,329 --> 01:03:25,875
-[George] Yeah. I'll take one.
-[Tony] Hmm. What's that?

973
01:03:25,916 --> 01:03:29,295
-A pimento and cheese sandwich, sir.
-Yeah, I'll try one of them.

974
01:03:32,089 --> 01:03:33,799
Oof. [groans]

975
01:03:40,556 --> 01:03:42,016
Sorry. Not for me.

976
01:03:46,562 --> 01:03:48,689
-[clinking]
-[chatter quietens]

977
01:03:48,731 --> 01:03:49,940
Here we go.

978
01:03:49,982 --> 01:03:54,403
Earlier this week, we asked our help
what Mr Shirley might like for supper.

979
01:03:54,445 --> 01:03:57,239
So the boys in the kitchen
whipped up a special menu

980
01:03:57,281 --> 01:03:59,492
in honor of our guest. Gentlemen.

981
01:04:00,618 --> 01:04:02,453
Home-cooked fried chicken!

982
01:04:02,495 --> 01:04:04,497
[applause and murmuring]

983
01:04:09,502 --> 01:04:12,963
There we go. Bring it in. Serve it up hot.

984
01:04:13,005 --> 01:04:15,049
[mid-tempo jazz]

985
01:04:37,113 --> 01:04:38,447
[music ends]

986
01:04:39,115 --> 01:04:41,617
[applause]

987
01:04:42,743 --> 01:04:45,371
Thank you. Thank you.

988
01:04:47,123 --> 01:04:49,166
We'll return after a brief intermission.

989
01:04:49,208 --> 01:04:51,252
-[quiet chatter]
-[woman laughing]

990
01:04:51,961 --> 01:04:56,590
-Excuse me, Don. Lovely work in there.
-Why, thank you.

991
01:04:56,632 --> 01:04:58,342
Uh, are you looking for the commode?

992
01:04:58,384 --> 01:05:00,428
-Yes. I...
-Yeah, here. Let me help you.

993
01:05:00,469 --> 01:05:02,346
It's right out there before that pine.

994
01:05:07,893 --> 01:05:09,437
I'd prefer not to use that.

995
01:05:09,478 --> 01:05:13,232
Well, don't be silly, Don.
It looks a lot worse from the outside.

996
01:05:13,274 --> 01:05:15,568
And I suppose you'd know from experience.

997
01:05:15,609 --> 01:05:17,695
Well, I've never had any complaints.

998
01:05:21,782 --> 01:05:25,411
Well, I could return to my motel
and use the facilities there...

999
01:05:26,454 --> 01:05:28,831
but that would take
at least a half an hour.

1000
01:05:32,835 --> 01:05:34,462
We don't mind waiting.

1001
01:05:36,547 --> 01:05:38,966
Why don't I just pull over?
You can piss in the woods.

1002
01:05:39,550 --> 01:05:41,093
Animals go in the woods.

1003
01:05:41,135 --> 01:05:43,846
It's gonna be at least 20 minutes
all the way back to your motel.

1004
01:05:43,888 --> 01:05:47,099
So let's just get there,
so I can go back and finish the show.

1005
01:05:47,141 --> 01:05:49,769
[sighs] See? That's the difference
between you and me.

1006
01:05:49,810 --> 01:05:52,521
-I'd have zero problem going in the woods.
-I'm well aware.

1007
01:05:53,522 --> 01:05:56,400
What are you sore at me for?
I don't make the rules down here.

1008
01:05:56,442 --> 01:05:57,568
No?

1009
01:05:58,360 --> 01:05:59,695
Then who does?

1010
01:06:00,571 --> 01:06:04,200
Oh. You're saying
just cos I'm white and they're white?

1011
01:06:04,784 --> 01:06:07,286
You know, that's a very prejudiced thing
you just said there.

1012
01:06:07,328 --> 01:06:09,163
A very prejudiced thing.

1013
01:06:09,205 --> 01:06:11,999
I got more in common
with the Hymies at 2nd Avenue deli

1014
01:06:12,041 --> 01:06:15,252
-than with these hillbilly pricks here.
-Eyes on the road.

1015
01:06:15,294 --> 01:06:17,838
You always say that
when you don't like what I'm saying.

1016
01:06:17,880 --> 01:06:19,548
Eyes on the road!

1017
01:06:21,425 --> 01:06:25,179
-[chatter and laughter]
-[Tony] I don't get it.

1018
01:06:25,221 --> 01:06:28,182
How does he smile
and shake their hands like that?

1019
01:06:28,974 --> 01:06:32,686
They try to pull that outhouse shit on me,
I'd piss right on the living room floor.

1020
01:06:34,688 --> 01:06:36,398
Don't, don't do that.

1021
01:06:38,400 --> 01:06:40,611
We have many concert dates left.

1022
01:06:43,322 --> 01:06:44,824
Yeah. So?

1023
01:06:45,574 --> 01:06:47,952
You realize we're contractually obliged
to perform them?

1024
01:06:49,870 --> 01:06:52,665
Course I do.
You don't play, we don't get paid.

1025
01:06:53,499 --> 01:06:54,750
What's your point?

1026
01:06:54,792 --> 01:06:57,628
Ugly circumstances
are going to happen again.

1027
01:06:58,462 --> 01:07:00,005
So control yourself.

1028
01:07:00,798 --> 01:07:02,716
Don't lecture me, you rat.

1029
01:07:05,594 --> 01:07:08,556
Dr Shirley could have stayed up north,
getting rear-end kissed

1030
01:07:08,597 --> 01:07:11,225
at Park Avenue parties
for three times money.

1031
01:07:11,851 --> 01:07:13,811
But he ask for this.

1032
01:07:13,853 --> 01:07:15,938
[chatter continues]

1033
01:07:18,941 --> 01:07:20,109
Why?

1034
01:07:39,670 --> 01:07:41,630
What on God's green Earth are you doing?

1035
01:07:42,298 --> 01:07:45,718
-A letter.
-Looks more like a piecemeal ransom note.

1036
01:07:47,303 --> 01:07:48,304
May I?

1037
01:07:55,853 --> 01:08:00,691
<i>"Deer </i>Dolores."
D-E-A-R. This is an animal.

1038
01:08:00,733 --> 01:08:04,653
"I'm meeting all the highly leading
citizens of the town.

1039
01:08:06,155 --> 01:08:09,617
People that use big words, all of them.

1040
01:08:09,658 --> 01:08:12,036
But you know me, I get by.

1041
01:08:12,078 --> 01:08:15,998
I'm a good bullshiter."
Two T's in "bullshitter".

1042
01:08:17,166 --> 01:08:20,961
"As I'm writing this letter,
I'm eating potato chips

1043
01:08:21,003 --> 01:08:23,798
and I'm starting to get thirsty.

1044
01:08:24,840 --> 01:08:27,885
I washed my socks
and dried them on the TV.

1045
01:08:28,635 --> 01:08:32,430
I should have <i>brung </i>the iron."
You know this is pathetic, right?

1046
01:08:33,974 --> 01:08:36,936
-Tell me what you're trying to say.
-I don't know.

1047
01:08:38,269 --> 01:08:40,189
You know, I miss her and shit.

1048
01:08:40,231 --> 01:08:45,027
Then say that. But do it in a manner
that no-one else has ever done it before.

1049
01:08:45,568 --> 01:08:46,862
And without the profanity.

1050
01:08:47,988 --> 01:08:49,031
Something like, uh...

1051
01:08:50,825 --> 01:08:52,034
Put this down.

1052
01:08:54,829 --> 01:08:57,540
-Dear Dolores...
-Hold on. I'll start a new one.

1053
01:08:58,706 --> 01:09:01,460
D-E-A-R Dolores...

1054
01:09:03,921 --> 01:09:05,255
When I think of you...

1055
01:09:07,006 --> 01:09:10,510
I'm reminded
of the beautiful plains of Iowa.

1056
01:09:11,220 --> 01:09:12,930
What planes?

1057
01:09:13,514 --> 01:09:17,684
The plains. P-L-A-I-N-S.
Those big fields we saw.

1058
01:09:17,726 --> 01:09:21,147
Oh. Yeah, those were nice. Plains.

1059
01:09:22,439 --> 01:09:25,860
"Which is what they call

1060
01:09:25,901 --> 01:09:29,655
big fields around here."

1061
01:09:29,697 --> 01:09:31,573
Tony, no expounding.

1062
01:09:31,615 --> 01:09:33,701
-No what?
-Just write what I say.

1063
01:09:33,742 --> 01:09:35,536
No good.

1064
01:09:35,577 --> 01:09:37,662
The distance between us...

1065
01:09:39,706 --> 01:09:41,291
is breaking my spirit.

1066
01:09:42,751 --> 01:09:44,211
"Between us."

1067
01:09:45,045 --> 01:09:49,008
My time and experiences without you
are meaningless to me.

1068
01:09:49,550 --> 01:09:52,887
[birds chirping]

1069
01:09:53,554 --> 01:09:56,932
Falling in love with you
was the easiest thing I've ever done.

1070
01:09:57,558 --> 01:10:01,937
"Falling in love with you..."

1071
01:10:05,274 --> 01:10:08,736
[Tony] <i>...was the easiest thing
I have ever done.</i>

1072
01:10:08,778 --> 01:10:10,780
<i>Nothing matters to me but you.</i>

1073
01:10:11,739 --> 01:10:15,367
<i>And every day I'm alive,
I'm aware of this.</i>

1074
01:10:15,409 --> 01:10:17,161
<i>I loved you the day I met you</i>

1075
01:10:17,953 --> 01:10:22,583
<i>I love you today,
and I will love you the rest of my life.</i>

1076
01:10:22,625 --> 01:10:25,169
[piano playing mid-tempo]

1077
01:10:25,211 --> 01:10:27,880
So can I put, uh... "PS. Kiss the kids"?

1078
01:10:27,922 --> 01:10:30,716
-A PS?
-Yeah, like, at the end.

1079
01:10:32,176 --> 01:10:35,721
That's like clanging a cowbell
at the end of Shostakovich's "Seventh".

1080
01:10:37,556 --> 01:10:39,391
Right. So that's good.

1081
01:10:41,143 --> 01:10:42,520
It's perfect, Tony.

1082
01:10:46,565 --> 01:10:49,235
[Tony] Everybody talks
about Willie Mays, 1954.

1083
01:10:49,276 --> 01:10:51,779
It wasn't even the greatest catch
in the Polo Grounds.

1084
01:10:51,821 --> 01:10:56,158
That was Joe DiMaggio, 1936,
second game of the World Series.

1085
01:10:56,200 --> 01:10:58,619
Final out, 500 feet...

1086
01:11:02,581 --> 01:11:05,292
-You like that, Doc?
-That's a handsome suit.

1087
01:11:05,334 --> 01:11:06,794
-Sharp.
-Mm-hm.

1088
01:11:07,420 --> 01:11:09,255
[Tony] Guy looks just like you.

1089
01:11:10,464 --> 01:11:11,507
He does?

1090
01:11:13,259 --> 01:11:15,469
Well, size-wise. Yeah.

1091
01:11:16,345 --> 01:11:19,181
[Dr Shirley chuckles] He's about a 42.

1092
01:11:20,433 --> 01:11:23,310
-Why don't you try it on?
-Hmm...

1093
01:11:23,352 --> 01:11:26,021
What, you gotta wear
a tuxedo onstage every night?

1094
01:11:26,063 --> 01:11:27,898
You could mix it up a little, Doc.

1095
01:11:27,940 --> 01:11:30,901
Come on, let's see how it looks on you.
We got plenty of time.

1096
01:11:30,943 --> 01:11:32,611
[bell jingles]

1097
01:11:32,653 --> 01:11:35,239
-[music playing over radio]
-I'll be right back.

1098
01:11:36,157 --> 01:11:38,576
-How you doing?
-May I help you, sir?

1099
01:11:38,617 --> 01:11:41,954
Yeah, we want to try on that, uh,
beautiful gray suit in the window.

1100
01:11:41,996 --> 01:11:44,039
-You got it in a 42?
-Of course.

1101
01:11:47,460 --> 01:11:50,463
-That's the one.
-Dressing room is in the back, sir.

1102
01:11:51,255 --> 01:11:53,507
Thank you. I'll be just a moment.

1103
01:11:53,549 --> 01:11:56,135
Take your time, Doc.
I'll check out some ties for you.

1104
01:11:57,928 --> 01:12:02,016
Uh, excuse me.
You're not allowed to try that on.

1105
01:12:03,768 --> 01:12:04,977
I beg your pardon?

1106
01:12:05,019 --> 01:12:10,065
Uh, if you'd like to purchase it first,
we'd be happy to tailor it to your needs.

1107
01:12:12,318 --> 01:12:13,360
I see.

1108
01:12:19,992 --> 01:12:21,076
[bell jingles]

1109
01:12:27,333 --> 01:12:30,961
[up-tempo music]

1110
01:12:56,362 --> 01:12:57,738
[music ends]

1111
01:12:57,780 --> 01:13:00,199
[cheering and applause]

1112
01:13:02,827 --> 01:13:04,078
[grunts]

1113
01:13:07,498 --> 01:13:08,958
[phone ringing]

1114
01:13:16,173 --> 01:13:17,174
Yeah.

1115
01:13:19,009 --> 01:13:20,094
That's me.

1116
01:13:22,596 --> 01:13:26,684
[soft, dramatic music fades in]

1117
01:13:31,689 --> 01:13:35,067
Hey, Officer.
I got a call about Dr Shirley.

1118
01:13:36,110 --> 01:13:37,111
Come on.

1119
01:13:42,032 --> 01:13:43,409
His friend's here.

1120
01:13:45,119 --> 01:13:47,913
-[Dr Shirley] Thank you.
-[Tony sighs]

1121
01:13:51,041 --> 01:13:54,754
-Get a guy a towel, for Christ's sake!
-You a lawyer?

1122
01:13:54,795 --> 01:13:56,380
-No.
-Well, you should call one.

1123
01:13:56,422 --> 01:13:58,090
-We're taking your auntie in.
-For what?

1124
01:13:58,132 --> 01:14:00,342
Manager caught him and the other guy.

1125
01:14:05,055 --> 01:14:08,058
Well, can we get the cuffs off him,
let him put his pants on,

1126
01:14:08,100 --> 01:14:10,561
-we talk about this?
-Sure, we could.

1127
01:14:11,228 --> 01:14:12,521
But we ain't.

1128
01:14:12,563 --> 01:14:13,814
Okay, look.

1129
01:14:14,607 --> 01:14:17,902
We're out of here tomorrow morning.
You'll never see us again.

1130
01:14:17,943 --> 01:14:20,321
There's gotta be something
we can do to work this out.

1131
01:14:21,572 --> 01:14:25,034
What if you let him go and
I give you something to thank you?

1132
01:14:25,075 --> 01:14:27,661
[laughs] You bribing us?

1133
01:14:27,703 --> 01:14:29,497
No! Hell, no.

1134
01:14:29,538 --> 01:14:31,707
A gift. A thank you.

1135
01:14:32,291 --> 01:14:36,337
-[officer] What kind of thank you?
-[Tony] Like a...

1136
01:14:36,378 --> 01:14:39,590
You know, donation
to the police force, youse guys.

1137
01:14:40,674 --> 01:14:41,884
Whatever you want.

1138
01:14:42,927 --> 01:14:44,553
You like suits?

1139
01:14:44,595 --> 01:14:46,972
I was walking
through your nice town today,

1140
01:14:47,014 --> 01:14:49,225
and I seen a store that was selling suits.

1141
01:14:50,267 --> 01:14:51,560
<i>Primo </i>suits.

1142
01:14:51,602 --> 01:14:54,688
What if, as a thank you, a donation...

1143
01:14:55,731 --> 01:14:57,358
I buy youse each a suit?

1144
01:14:58,818 --> 01:15:02,446
You get all dressed up,
you take the wife out for dinner.

1145
01:15:02,488 --> 01:15:05,533
I mean, guys like you,
you work hard, you deserve it.

1146
01:15:13,833 --> 01:15:16,710
They were wrong for the way
they treated me and you rewarded them.

1147
01:15:18,629 --> 01:15:21,257
I was hired to get you
from one show to the next.

1148
01:15:21,298 --> 01:15:23,259
How I do it shouldn't matter to you.

1149
01:15:23,300 --> 01:15:26,345
-I just wish you hadn't paid 'em off.
-I did what I had to do.

1150
01:15:27,680 --> 01:15:29,932
You know, if this got out,
it would kill your career.

1151
01:15:29,974 --> 01:15:30,975
Okay, Tony.

1152
01:15:32,017 --> 01:15:34,145
I need you to stop it
with the phony altruism

1153
01:15:34,186 --> 01:15:37,022
-and concern for my career.
-What the hell does that mean?

1154
01:15:37,064 --> 01:15:39,066
You were only thinking
about yourself back there,

1155
01:15:39,108 --> 01:15:42,027
because you know if I miss a show,
it'll come out of your pocketbook.

1156
01:15:42,069 --> 01:15:45,072
Of course I don't want you to miss a show,
you ungrateful bastard!

1157
01:15:45,114 --> 01:15:46,907
You think I'm doing this for my health?

1158
01:15:47,658 --> 01:15:51,620
Tonight, I saved your ass.
So show a little appreciation, maybe.

1159
01:15:52,246 --> 01:15:54,749
Besides, I told you
never to go nowhere without me!

1160
01:15:56,625 --> 01:15:59,211
I assumed you'd want this
to be the exception.

1161
01:15:59,253 --> 01:16:02,256
[soft ambient music fades in]

1162
01:16:12,057 --> 01:16:13,726
[car door opens]

1163
01:16:14,727 --> 01:16:16,061
[door closes]

1164
01:16:16,103 --> 01:16:19,190
[soft ambient music continues]

1165
01:16:31,702 --> 01:16:33,287
[engine off]

1166
01:16:34,747 --> 01:16:38,501
Want me to get some... makeup
or something for the show tomorrow?

1167
01:16:38,542 --> 01:16:40,127
No, I'm fine.

1168
01:16:40,169 --> 01:16:43,464
-You sure? Bruise kind of shows.
-I said I'm fine.

1169
01:16:44,840 --> 01:16:45,883
Okay.

1170
01:16:49,136 --> 01:16:50,137
[car door closes]

1171
01:16:54,141 --> 01:16:57,353
-[man 1] He didn't ask me to do that.
-[man 2] Dom, that's what he told me.

1172
01:16:57,394 --> 01:17:00,397
He didn't ask me. Oh...

1173
01:17:00,439 --> 01:17:03,275
-Tony Lip. What the hell?
-Dominic, Mags.

1174
01:17:03,317 --> 01:17:05,820
-What are you guys doing around here?
-Brooklyn sent us down.

1175
01:17:05,861 --> 01:17:08,072
-Take care of a few things.
-Yeah.

1176
01:17:10,783 --> 01:17:12,576
[in Italian]

1177
01:17:16,705 --> 01:17:18,249
[laughter]

1178
01:17:43,023 --> 01:17:44,567
I'm working here.

1179
01:17:53,200 --> 01:17:55,494
Sorry, Doc.
They're some friends from New York.

1180
01:17:56,495 --> 01:17:59,373
-Hey, can you get Dr Shirley's luggage?
-All right.

1181
01:18:03,919 --> 01:18:07,298
[soft, dramatic music fades in]

1182
01:18:20,936 --> 01:18:24,648
[music intensifies]

1183
01:18:24,690 --> 01:18:26,817
[chatter]

1184
01:18:32,615 --> 01:18:34,825
Called his room. Be down in a minute.

1185
01:18:36,619 --> 01:18:38,662
-[sighs]
-[lock clicks]

1186
01:18:38,704 --> 01:18:40,247
[door rattles]

1187
01:18:44,710 --> 01:18:46,754
-Hey, Doc.
-Where are you off to?

1188
01:18:49,131 --> 01:18:52,259
I'm just going downstairs.
To have a drink.

1189
01:18:53,636 --> 01:18:55,763
[in Italian]

1190
01:19:03,854 --> 01:19:07,316
Tony... I think you're doing
a wonderful job.

1191
01:19:09,110 --> 01:19:10,111
So...

1192
01:19:11,487 --> 01:19:14,281
I'd like to formally offer you
the position of my road manager.

1193
01:19:15,074 --> 01:19:18,577
With the title also comes
more responsibility, but...

1194
01:19:20,162 --> 01:19:21,789
that also means a raise in pay.

1195
01:19:22,706 --> 01:19:24,417
No. No.

1196
01:19:24,458 --> 01:19:25,709
No, thanks.

1197
01:19:27,670 --> 01:19:30,756
We agreed on 125 a week.

1198
01:19:30,798 --> 01:19:33,342
Plus expenses. That's our deal.

1199
01:19:33,384 --> 01:19:34,635
Right?

1200
01:19:36,053 --> 01:19:40,391
[chuckles] I ain't going nowhere, Doc.
I, I was just going down to tell them.

1201
01:19:45,980 --> 01:19:48,941
[chuckles, sighs]

1202
01:19:50,901 --> 01:19:52,194
Tony.

1203
01:19:53,988 --> 01:19:57,324
[soft ambient music]

1204
01:19:57,366 --> 01:19:59,076
I'm sorry about last night.

1205
01:20:03,289 --> 01:20:04,623
Don't worry about it.

1206
01:20:06,792 --> 01:20:09,879
I've been working nightclubs
in New York City my whole life.

1207
01:20:09,920 --> 01:20:11,422
I know it's a...

1208
01:20:12,715 --> 01:20:14,258
complicated world.

1209
01:20:14,300 --> 01:20:16,886
[music intensifies]

1210
01:20:27,104 --> 01:20:29,398
So where'd you learn
how to play like that?

1211
01:20:29,440 --> 01:20:31,192
-My mother.
-Your mother?

1212
01:20:31,233 --> 01:20:32,985
-Really?
-Mm-hm.

1213
01:20:35,029 --> 01:20:37,323
She taught me how to play
on an old spinet.

1214
01:20:38,741 --> 01:20:43,245
Soon as I could walk, we'd...
travel around the Florida Panhandle,

1215
01:20:44,121 --> 01:20:46,916
put on my little shows
in parishes and halls.

1216
01:20:46,957 --> 01:20:49,502
Fortunately, a man who had seen me play

1217
01:20:49,543 --> 01:20:52,630
arranged for me to study
at the Leningrad Conservatory of Music.

1218
01:20:53,506 --> 01:20:55,841
I was the first Negro ever accepted there.

1219
01:20:55,883 --> 01:20:58,344
That's where they taught you
all them songs you play?

1220
01:20:58,385 --> 01:21:00,596
Actually, I was trained
to play classical music.

1221
01:21:01,347 --> 01:21:05,309
Brahms, Franz Liszt, Beethoven, Chopin.

1222
01:21:06,811 --> 01:21:08,729
It's all I ever wanted to play.

1223
01:21:10,022 --> 01:21:12,191
But I was persuaded by my record company

1224
01:21:12,233 --> 01:21:14,944
to pursue a career
in popular music instead.

1225
01:21:15,986 --> 01:21:18,114
They insisted
that audiences would never accept

1226
01:21:18,155 --> 01:21:20,157
a Negro pianist on a classical stage.

1227
01:21:21,200 --> 01:21:24,078
Wanted to turn me into
just another colored entertainer.

1228
01:21:25,746 --> 01:21:29,208
You know, the guy
who's smoking while he's playing

1229
01:21:29,250 --> 01:21:31,419
and sets a glass of whisky on his piano,

1230
01:21:31,460 --> 01:21:35,673
and then complains because
he's not respected like Arthur Rubinstein.

1231
01:21:35,714 --> 01:21:38,884
[chuckling]
You don't see Arthur Rubinstein

1232
01:21:38,926 --> 01:21:40,928
putting a glass of whisky on his piano.

1233
01:21:43,180 --> 01:21:46,475
I don't know. Personally, I think
if you'd stuck to the classic stuff,

1234
01:21:46,517 --> 01:21:49,520
-it would've been a big mistake.
-A mistake?

1235
01:21:49,562 --> 01:21:52,815
Performing the music
I trained my entire life to play?

1236
01:21:52,857 --> 01:21:57,027
Trained? What are you, a seal?
People love what you do.

1237
01:21:57,611 --> 01:21:59,697
Anyone could sound like Beethoven or...

1238
01:21:59,738 --> 01:22:02,116
"Joe Pan" or them other guys you said.

1239
01:22:02,158 --> 01:22:05,786
But <i>your </i>music... what <i>you </i>do...

1240
01:22:08,080 --> 01:22:09,331
Only <i>you </i>can do that.

1241
01:22:12,626 --> 01:22:13,711
Thank you, Tony.

1242
01:22:18,883 --> 01:22:21,010
But not everyone can play Chopin.

1243
01:22:22,845 --> 01:22:24,263
Not like I can.

1244
01:22:25,765 --> 01:22:28,434
[Bobby Page &amp; The Riff Raffs]
<i>♪ I love my baby... </i>♪

1245
01:22:28,476 --> 01:22:30,853
[Dr Shirley]
<i>The trees have shed their leafy clothing,</i>

1246
01:22:30,895 --> 01:22:34,273
and their colors have faded
to grays and browns.

1247
01:22:34,315 --> 01:22:38,235
"I saw millions of trees
all dusted with snow,

1248
01:22:38,277 --> 01:22:39,987
just like out of a fairy tale."

1249
01:22:40,029 --> 01:22:42,406
He's so expressive!

1250
01:22:43,240 --> 01:22:46,660
Got to admit,
Lip's letters... they're not bad.

1251
01:22:46,702 --> 01:22:50,748
Oh, well, it's in the family.
They say our great-great-great-grandfather

1252
01:22:50,790 --> 01:22:53,084
helped Da Vinci with the Sixteen Chapel.

1253
01:22:53,125 --> 01:22:55,586
-You mean Michelangelo.
-Right.

1254
01:22:55,628 --> 01:22:57,880
What does Michelangelo have to do
with writing letters?

1255
01:22:57,922 --> 01:23:00,549
I'm just saying, we're an arty family.

1256
01:23:00,591 --> 01:23:05,054
"I will count the hours,
minutes and seconds

1257
01:23:05,096 --> 01:23:07,139
until you are in my arms.

1258
01:23:07,181 --> 01:23:10,518
Love you, Tony.
PS. Kiss the kids."

1259
01:23:12,103 --> 01:23:14,063
-John!
-Yeah?

1260
01:23:14,647 --> 01:23:16,398
-I want a letter.
-Yeah.

1261
01:23:16,440 --> 01:23:19,193
-Soon as you make a meal.
-[chuckling]

1262
01:23:19,235 --> 01:23:21,821
[lively piano music]

1263
01:23:29,036 --> 01:23:32,164
[laughs]

1264
01:23:32,206 --> 01:23:35,042
-That was a bullshit artist!
-Eyes forward, Tony.

1265
01:23:40,047 --> 01:23:41,966
[piano music continues]

1266
01:24:00,151 --> 01:24:01,902
[Dr Shirley] Tony!

1267
01:24:01,944 --> 01:24:05,823
All right, everybody,
let's give our finest Louisiana welcome

1268
01:24:05,865 --> 01:24:08,701
to Don Shirley and the Don Shirley Trio.

1269
01:24:08,742 --> 01:24:11,078
[applause]

1270
01:24:22,131 --> 01:24:25,593
-[music ends]
-[applause]

1271
01:24:35,436 --> 01:24:37,646
[grunts] Your mother's ass.

1272
01:24:37,688 --> 01:24:39,899
Can't see shit.

1273
01:24:39,940 --> 01:24:41,942
[Tony grunts]

1274
01:24:47,573 --> 01:24:49,074
What the hell's this guy doing?

1275
01:24:49,992 --> 01:24:52,787
[siren wailing]

1276
01:24:52,828 --> 01:24:54,955
Son of a bitch.

1277
01:25:07,218 --> 01:25:09,011
License and papers.

1278
01:25:10,054 --> 01:25:11,972
[Tony] Am I glad to see you!

1279
01:25:12,014 --> 01:25:16,310
We had to turn off the main road,
and, uh... now we're lost.

1280
01:25:18,813 --> 01:25:21,732
-Step out of the car.
-What'd I do?

1281
01:25:21,774 --> 01:25:23,442
Out of the car!

1282
01:25:29,865 --> 01:25:31,700
-[sighs]
-[door closes]

1283
01:25:35,204 --> 01:25:38,124
-Why are you on this road?
-I told you.

1284
01:25:38,165 --> 01:25:41,335
We had to make a detour and we got lost.

1285
01:25:46,173 --> 01:25:48,050
And why are <i>you </i>driving <i>him</i>?

1286
01:25:48,968 --> 01:25:50,469
He's my boss.

1287
01:25:56,559 --> 01:26:00,187
He can't be out here at night.
This is a sundown town.

1288
01:26:00,229 --> 01:26:01,647
What's that?

1289
01:26:03,566 --> 01:26:06,193
Get him out of the car and check his ID.

1290
01:26:06,235 --> 01:26:08,654
Oh, come on, it's pouring rain.

1291
01:26:08,696 --> 01:26:11,282
Sir, I can just get it right here
through the window--

1292
01:26:11,323 --> 01:26:14,410
-Get him out of the car.
-Come on, get out, now.

1293
01:26:14,452 --> 01:26:16,162
Get out, now. Get out!

1294
01:26:17,121 --> 01:26:18,414
Got ID?

1295
01:26:21,208 --> 01:26:23,002
How you say this last name?

1296
01:26:24,003 --> 01:26:25,254
Vallelonga.

1297
01:26:26,088 --> 01:26:28,215
Yeah, what kind of name is that?

1298
01:26:28,257 --> 01:26:29,759
It's Italian.

1299
01:26:30,468 --> 01:26:32,887
Oh. Oh, I see.

1300
01:26:32,928 --> 01:26:35,014
That's why you're driving <i>him </i>around.

1301
01:26:37,099 --> 01:26:39,477
You're half a nigger yourself. [grunts]

1302
01:26:40,519 --> 01:26:42,772
Hands in the air! Now! Now!

1303
01:26:46,776 --> 01:26:48,152
[Dr Shirley] Excuse me.

1304
01:26:49,570 --> 01:26:51,197
[Dr Shirley clears throat]

1305
01:26:52,364 --> 01:26:53,783
Excuse me, sirs.

1306
01:26:56,410 --> 01:26:58,829
I, I understand
why my associate is being held,

1307
01:26:58,871 --> 01:27:00,956
but what exactly am I being charged with?

1308
01:27:05,002 --> 01:27:06,879
You seem like reasonable men.

1309
01:27:07,713 --> 01:27:11,383
Perhaps you could let me out, so that
we could discuss the situation further.

1310
01:27:11,425 --> 01:27:15,763
Just put the apple butter away, boy.
You ain't going nowhere no time soon.

1311
01:27:17,139 --> 01:27:19,433
You cannot hold me without cause.

1312
01:27:19,475 --> 01:27:23,562
Oh, I got cause.
Cos you let the sun set on your black ass.

1313
01:27:25,523 --> 01:27:29,735
I want to speak to my lawyer.
I want my call.

1314
01:27:29,777 --> 01:27:32,571
This is a flagrant violation of my rights.

1315
01:27:33,864 --> 01:27:34,907
You know...

1316
01:27:36,617 --> 01:27:40,204
he does have, uh... rights.

1317
01:27:45,459 --> 01:27:47,586
Give the Negro his goddamn phone call.

1318
01:27:48,671 --> 01:27:49,922
You happy?

1319
01:27:52,758 --> 01:27:54,718
[lifts receiver]

1320
01:27:54,760 --> 01:27:57,555
You know a lawyer? Call him.

1321
01:28:09,191 --> 01:28:12,820
[officer] I walk up to the car and I say:
"Sir, you know how fast you were going?"

1322
01:28:12,862 --> 01:28:15,406
He says: "I'm sorry, Officer.
I didn't mean to speed, but..."

1323
01:28:15,448 --> 01:28:19,160
[Dr Shirley] As my mother always said:
"What kind of brand-new fool are you?"

1324
01:28:19,201 --> 01:28:20,828
Look at them over there.

1325
01:28:21,662 --> 01:28:23,581
Take a good look at the officer you hit.

1326
01:28:23,622 --> 01:28:26,125
Look at him.
He's over there having a grand old time,

1327
01:28:26,167 --> 01:28:30,254
chatting up with his pals,
enjoying a nice cup of coffee.

1328
01:28:31,088 --> 01:28:32,381
And where are you?

1329
01:28:32,423 --> 01:28:35,301
In here, with me, who did nothing.

1330
01:28:36,177 --> 01:28:38,387
Yet I'm the one who pays the price.

1331
01:28:38,429 --> 01:28:40,639
I'm the one who's gonna miss
the Birmingham show.

1332
01:28:40,681 --> 01:28:44,143
Hey, I'm gonna lose a lot of money, too,
if you don't play Birmingham.

1333
01:28:44,185 --> 01:28:47,271
So that little temper tantrum,
was it worth it?

1334
01:28:48,606 --> 01:28:49,565
Hmm?

1335
01:28:50,858 --> 01:28:52,651
You never win with violence, Tony.

1336
01:28:52,693 --> 01:28:55,070
You only win
when you maintain your dignity.

1337
01:28:55,112 --> 01:28:57,823
Dignity always prevails.

1338
01:28:59,200 --> 01:29:02,203
And tonight, because of you, we did not.

1339
01:29:03,996 --> 01:29:05,915
[phone rings]

1340
01:29:07,458 --> 01:29:09,460
I wouldn't touch that mattress, Doc.

1341
01:29:09,502 --> 01:29:11,879
-[phone rings]
-[officer] Maryville Police.

1342
01:29:15,049 --> 01:29:16,217
No, sir.

1343
01:29:16,967 --> 01:29:18,469
No, no, I, I'm not, sir.

1344
01:29:19,762 --> 01:29:21,680
Yes, sir. He's right here, sir. Yes, sir.

1345
01:29:22,473 --> 01:29:24,391
-Yes, sir.
-Give me.

1346
01:29:25,684 --> 01:29:27,353
Chief Pratt. Who's this?

1347
01:29:27,394 --> 01:29:29,146
Baloney.

1348
01:29:29,188 --> 01:29:31,607
[muffled shouting over the phone]

1349
01:29:31,649 --> 01:29:34,777
Yes, sir. I can hear it now, Governor.

1350
01:29:36,278 --> 01:29:37,404
[officer] Uh...

1351
01:29:38,739 --> 01:29:40,658
No, sir, I'm sorry. I...

1352
01:29:40,699 --> 01:29:43,077
No, of course
I can recognize your voice, it's...

1353
01:29:43,119 --> 01:29:46,288
[soft music fades in]

1354
01:29:46,330 --> 01:29:47,289
Sir?

1355
01:29:48,541 --> 01:29:51,794
You're saying the boy
we got locked up called whom?

1356
01:29:55,131 --> 01:29:56,966
Oh, and he called you.

1357
01:29:57,007 --> 01:30:01,720
No. Now, sir, an officer was assaulted
in the line of duty.

1358
01:30:01,762 --> 01:30:04,723
[soft music intensifies]

1359
01:30:04,765 --> 01:30:05,850
No, sir. No.

1360
01:30:05,891 --> 01:30:09,520
I don't want no National Guard
coming down here, neither, sir.

1361
01:30:10,604 --> 01:30:12,356
I'll get to it immediately, Governor.

1362
01:30:13,399 --> 01:30:15,484
Good night to you and the missus.

1363
01:30:20,072 --> 01:30:22,032
-Get 'em out.
-What?

1364
01:30:22,074 --> 01:30:25,578
-Cut 'em goddamn loose.
-That dago wop hit me!

1365
01:30:25,619 --> 01:30:29,290
You want to keep your goddamn job?
Then you do what I goddamn tell you to do

1366
01:30:29,331 --> 01:30:31,333
when I goddamn tell you to do it!

1367
01:30:31,375 --> 01:30:34,128
And I'm telling you
to get 'em the goddamn out!

1368
01:30:34,170 --> 01:30:35,629
Who the hell did you call?

1369
01:30:38,841 --> 01:30:41,135
Bobby Kennedy just saved our asses.

1370
01:30:41,177 --> 01:30:43,262
<i>Madonna</i>. How great is that?

1371
01:30:44,388 --> 01:30:47,475
It's not great. It's not great at all.

1372
01:30:47,516 --> 01:30:49,894
-It's humiliating.
-The hell you talking about?

1373
01:30:49,935 --> 01:30:51,937
We were screwed. Now we ain't.

1374
01:30:52,813 --> 01:30:55,191
And I just put the Attorney General
of the United States

1375
01:30:55,232 --> 01:30:57,902
-in an incredibly awkward position.
-So what?

1376
01:30:57,943 --> 01:31:00,529
That's what the guy gets paid for.
What else he got to do?

1377
01:31:01,197 --> 01:31:04,658
That man and his brother
are trying to change this country.

1378
01:31:04,700 --> 01:31:06,202
That's what else "he got to do"!

1379
01:31:07,828 --> 01:31:09,872
Now he thinks I'm some kind of...

1380
01:31:11,749 --> 01:31:16,170
Calling from some... backwoods swamp jail,
asking to attenuate assault charges?

1381
01:31:16,212 --> 01:31:17,838
Who does that?

1382
01:31:17,880 --> 01:31:21,425
Garbage. That's who.
You shouldn't have hit him.

1383
01:31:21,467 --> 01:31:24,970
I didn't like the way he was treating you.
Making you stand out in the rain.

1384
01:31:25,012 --> 01:31:27,848
Please, you hit him
because of what he called <i>you</i>.

1385
01:31:28,641 --> 01:31:30,810
I've had to endure
that kind of talk my entire life.

1386
01:31:30,851 --> 01:31:32,812
You could take it for at least one night.

1387
01:31:32,853 --> 01:31:35,606
What, I can't get mad
at what he was saying cos I ain't black?

1388
01:31:35,648 --> 01:31:38,067
-Christ, I'm blacker than you are.
-Excuse me?

1389
01:31:38,109 --> 01:31:40,361
You don't know shit about your own people.

1390
01:31:40,402 --> 01:31:43,572
What they eat,
how they talk, how they live.

1391
01:31:43,614 --> 01:31:45,449
You don't even know who Little Richard is.

1392
01:31:45,491 --> 01:31:48,661
So knowing who Little Richard is
makes you blacker than me?

1393
01:31:48,702 --> 01:31:51,122
Oh, Tony, I wish
you could hear yourself sometimes.

1394
01:31:51,163 --> 01:31:52,873
You wouldn't talk so damn much.

1395
01:31:52,915 --> 01:31:55,960
Bullshit. I know exactly who <i>I </i>am.

1396
01:31:56,460 --> 01:31:59,422
I'm the guy who lived in the same
neighborhood in the Bronx my entire life

1397
01:31:59,463 --> 01:32:02,508
with my mother, my father, my brother,
and now my wife and kids.

1398
01:32:02,550 --> 01:32:05,302
That's it. That's who I am.
I'm the asshole

1399
01:32:05,344 --> 01:32:08,597
who has to hustle every goddamn day
to put food on the table.

1400
01:32:08,639 --> 01:32:11,600
You, Mr Big Shot,
you live on top of a castle,

1401
01:32:11,642 --> 01:32:14,395
traveling around the world
doing concerts for rich people.

1402
01:32:14,437 --> 01:32:17,106
I live on the streets.
You sit on a throne.

1403
01:32:17,148 --> 01:32:19,775
So, yeah, my world is
way more blacker than yours.

1404
01:32:21,902 --> 01:32:24,113
-Pull over.
-What?

1405
01:32:24,155 --> 01:32:25,322
Pull over.

1406
01:32:25,364 --> 01:32:27,908
-I ain't pulling over.
-Stop the car, Tony!

1407
01:32:30,536 --> 01:32:32,371
-What?
-[door opens]

1408
01:32:32,413 --> 01:32:33,581
What are you doing?

1409
01:32:34,540 --> 01:32:35,499
Doc?

1410
01:32:37,835 --> 01:32:40,921
Doc, what the hell are you doing? Doc.

1411
01:32:40,963 --> 01:32:45,468
-Get back in the car.
-Yes, I live in a castle, Tony! Alone.

1412
01:32:47,803 --> 01:32:49,972
And rich white people pay me
to play piano for them,

1413
01:32:50,014 --> 01:32:53,225
because it makes them feel cultured.
But as soon as I step off that stage,

1414
01:32:53,267 --> 01:32:55,686
I go right back to being
just another nigger to them.

1415
01:32:56,937 --> 01:32:58,647
Because that is their true culture.

1416
01:32:59,774 --> 01:33:02,818
And I suffer that slight alone,
because I'm not accepted by my own people,

1417
01:33:02,860 --> 01:33:04,445
cos I'm not like them, either.

1418
01:33:05,613 --> 01:33:08,282
So if I'm not black enough,
and if I'm not white enough,

1419
01:33:08,324 --> 01:33:11,327
and if I'm not man enough,
then tell me, Tony, what am I?

1420
01:33:11,994 --> 01:33:14,455
[soft ambient music]

1421
01:33:27,802 --> 01:33:29,428
[car door closes]

1422
01:33:29,470 --> 01:33:32,556
[music continues]

1423
01:33:46,112 --> 01:33:47,780
I need some sleep.

1424
01:33:51,408 --> 01:33:52,493
All right.

1425
01:33:53,411 --> 01:33:56,372
I'll stop at the next place we see
and sneak you into my room.

1426
01:33:56,956 --> 01:33:58,499
No. No.

1427
01:33:58,541 --> 01:34:01,502
I refuse to stay in an establishment
where I'm not welcome.

1428
01:34:04,213 --> 01:34:06,048
Yeah? Okay.

1429
01:34:06,090 --> 01:34:09,093
[soft ambient music fades out]

1430
01:34:24,316 --> 01:34:26,277
Tony, do you have to smoke everywhere?

1431
01:34:29,071 --> 01:34:30,906
I didn't know it bothered you.

1432
01:34:30,948 --> 01:34:32,575
You should've told me.

1433
01:34:33,909 --> 01:34:36,245
All you gotta do is say the word, Doc.

1434
01:34:40,166 --> 01:34:41,500
[sighs]

1435
01:34:43,335 --> 01:34:44,837
-[ear pops]
-[grunts]

1436
01:34:49,175 --> 01:34:52,470
You do realize you'll be home
before that letter arrives.

1437
01:34:52,511 --> 01:34:53,596
Yeah, I know.

1438
01:34:54,263 --> 01:34:57,224
Just thought I'd bring it with me.
Save on stamps.

1439
01:34:57,725 --> 01:34:58,851
All right.

1440
01:34:59,769 --> 01:35:01,645
Tony, give it here. I'll fix it.

1441
01:35:03,022 --> 01:35:07,026
No offense, Doc,
but I think I got the hang of it now.

1442
01:35:14,450 --> 01:35:15,743
"Dear Dolores,

1443
01:35:15,785 --> 01:35:18,412
sometimes you remind me of a house.

1444
01:35:22,083 --> 01:35:24,335
A house with beautiful lights on it...

1445
01:35:25,419 --> 01:35:27,421
where everyone is happy inside."

1446
01:35:27,463 --> 01:35:30,841
[soft ambient music fades in]

1447
01:35:30,883 --> 01:35:33,010
[chuckles softly]

1448
01:35:33,052 --> 01:35:35,471
Yes, Tony. You got it.

1449
01:35:36,514 --> 01:35:39,308
Yeah? [chuckles]

1450
01:35:39,350 --> 01:35:40,518
Thanks.

1451
01:35:43,896 --> 01:35:48,109
Hey, Doc, thanks
for helping me with, uh, the letters.

1452
01:35:48,901 --> 01:35:50,569
You're really good at writing 'em.

1453
01:35:51,403 --> 01:35:52,738
My pleasure, Tony.

1454
01:35:54,907 --> 01:35:57,701
You know, um, when you get home,
maybe you should write...

1455
01:35:57,743 --> 01:35:59,370
write one to your brother.

1456
01:36:00,413 --> 01:36:02,498
[music continues]

1457
01:36:02,540 --> 01:36:05,042
He knows where I am
if he ever wants to reconnect.

1458
01:36:05,668 --> 01:36:08,003
Eh. I wouldn't wait.

1459
01:36:09,922 --> 01:36:14,802
You know... world's full of lonely people
afraid to make the first move.

1460
01:36:22,476 --> 01:36:25,104
Yeah, I'll finish this tomorrow.

1461
01:36:32,653 --> 01:36:33,904
[coughs]

1462
01:36:36,282 --> 01:36:40,119
You know, Doc, something's been
eating at me this whole trip.

1463
01:36:40,161 --> 01:36:41,370
Hmm?

1464
01:36:42,163 --> 01:36:44,248
[soft ambient music fades out]

1465
01:36:44,290 --> 01:36:46,625
That Titsburgh was a major disappointment.

1466
01:36:46,667 --> 01:36:49,462
I didn't notice any difference at all.
Did you?

1467
01:36:49,962 --> 01:36:51,839
Good night, Tony.

1468
01:36:51,881 --> 01:36:55,342
["O Come All Ye Faithful Jazz Trio"
playing]

1469
01:37:04,059 --> 01:37:06,771
-[man 1] Good evening.
-[man 2] Welcome, welcome. Come on in.

1470
01:37:09,690 --> 01:37:12,109
-[Dr Shirley] All righty.
-[Tony sighs]

1471
01:37:14,445 --> 01:37:18,199
Welcome, Mr Shirley.
Graham Kindell, I'm the general manager.

1472
01:37:18,240 --> 01:37:21,410
-It is a pleasure to meet you.
-Thank you, Mr Kindell.

1473
01:37:21,452 --> 01:37:24,038
-This is Mr Tony Vallelonga.
-Nice to meeting you, Tony.

1474
01:37:24,080 --> 01:37:26,415
-How you doing?
-Let's keep the car right here in our...

1475
01:37:26,457 --> 01:37:29,085
"guest of honor" spot.
Right this way, gentlemen.

1476
01:37:29,126 --> 01:37:30,961
-[Tony] Hmm. Nice.
-How was your drive up?

1477
01:37:31,003 --> 01:37:33,089
-[Dr Shirley] Oh, it was wonderful.
-Good to hear.

1478
01:37:33,130 --> 01:37:36,425
As you can imagine, our Christmas show
is our biggest show of the year,

1479
01:37:36,467 --> 01:37:38,969
and we are so happy
to have you here, Mr Shirley.

1480
01:37:39,011 --> 01:37:42,056
So if you need anything,
anything at all, you let me know.

1481
01:37:42,098 --> 01:37:44,391
-Mm-hm. Thank you.
-Now, here we are.

1482
01:37:44,433 --> 01:37:47,561
We got about an hour before showtime.
Any questions?

1483
01:37:48,312 --> 01:37:49,855
Where's the restaurant?

1484
01:37:49,897 --> 01:37:53,776
Well, you continue down the hall here,
Tony, to the right and across the lobby.

1485
01:37:53,818 --> 01:37:55,986
-Good luck. Break a leg.
-Thank you.

1486
01:37:58,322 --> 01:38:01,450
Well, he said we got an hour.
You must be starving, Doc.

1487
01:38:01,492 --> 01:38:03,285
Go ahead. I'll meet you there.

1488
01:38:19,552 --> 01:38:21,679
["O Christmas Tree" playing on piano]

1489
01:38:29,520 --> 01:38:30,729
May we join you?

1490
01:38:32,064 --> 01:38:33,607
Mm. Go ahead.

1491
01:38:39,822 --> 01:38:41,282
Cocktail, gentlemen?

1492
01:38:41,323 --> 01:38:43,534
-I'm good.
-Three shots vodka.

1493
01:38:44,368 --> 01:38:45,494
Oh.

1494
01:38:45,536 --> 01:38:49,081
Last show. Cold War over, time for truce.

1495
01:38:51,000 --> 01:38:55,212
-Is Dr Shirley in his dressing room?
-Yeah. More like half a broom closet.

1496
01:38:56,005 --> 01:38:58,382
Tell you, I don't know
how he puts up with that shit.

1497
01:39:02,845 --> 01:39:05,556
Six years ago, in 1956,

1498
01:39:06,515 --> 01:39:09,059
Nat King Cole was invited to perform

1499
01:39:09,101 --> 01:39:11,687
at the Municipal Auditorium
here in Birmingham.

1500
01:39:13,022 --> 01:39:17,860
Mr Cole was the first Negro asked to play
at a white establishment in this city.

1501
01:39:17,902 --> 01:39:20,613
As soon as he started playing,
a group of men attack him

1502
01:39:20,654 --> 01:39:22,323
for playing white people's music.

1503
01:39:24,283 --> 01:39:25,868
They pull him off stage...

1504
01:39:26,994 --> 01:39:28,370
and beat him badly.

1505
01:39:29,371 --> 01:39:30,664
Jesus Christ.

1506
01:39:34,585 --> 01:39:39,090
You asked me once:
"Why Dr Shirley does this?"

1507
01:39:40,424 --> 01:39:44,053
I tell you. Because genius is not enough.

1508
01:39:44,929 --> 01:39:47,848
It takes courage
to change people's hearts.

1509
01:39:55,523 --> 01:39:56,357
Thanks.

1510
01:39:58,067 --> 01:39:59,276
[George] Thank you.

1511
01:40:00,820 --> 01:40:02,613
No? <i>Nazdarovye!</i>

1512
01:40:03,948 --> 01:40:05,157
<i>Danke schön.</i>

1513
01:40:07,660 --> 01:40:09,829
-[Dr Shirley] Good evening.
-Can I help you?

1514
01:40:09,870 --> 01:40:10,871
Oh, um...

1515
01:40:14,125 --> 01:40:16,127
Um, there. Some friends of mine.

1516
01:40:16,168 --> 01:40:18,796
Uh, y-you... you can't come in here.

1517
01:40:19,964 --> 01:40:21,465
[Tony groans]

1518
01:40:27,513 --> 01:40:29,598
-I understand, but...
-Hey. What's going on?

1519
01:40:30,391 --> 01:40:34,645
This... gentleman says
that I'm not permitted to dine here.

1520
01:40:34,687 --> 01:40:36,814
No, you don't understand.
He's playing tonight.

1521
01:40:36,856 --> 01:40:39,275
-He's the main event. Come on.
-I'm sorry, but...

1522
01:40:39,316 --> 01:40:42,445
-It is the policy of the restaurant.
-Everything all right?

1523
01:40:42,486 --> 01:40:46,115
Uh, no, it's not all right. This guy's
saying Dr Shirley can't eat here.

1524
01:40:47,074 --> 01:40:49,493
Oh, well, I apologize, but... [sighs]

1525
01:40:49,535 --> 01:40:53,247
...these are long-standing traditions,
club rules. I'm sure you understand.

1526
01:40:53,289 --> 01:40:55,583
No, I do not understand.

1527
01:40:55,624 --> 01:40:58,919
In 45 minutes, I will be up there
on that stage entertaining your guests.

1528
01:40:58,961 --> 01:41:00,504
Yet I can't eat here?

1529
01:41:00,546 --> 01:41:02,923
[sighs] I'm sorry.

1530
01:41:02,965 --> 01:41:05,926
Wait a minute.
Are you telling me the bozos in his band

1531
01:41:05,968 --> 01:41:09,805
and all these people who came here
to see him play, they can eat here?

1532
01:41:09,847 --> 01:41:12,892
But the star of the show,
the parking spot of honor, he can't?

1533
01:41:14,143 --> 01:41:15,644
I'm afraid not.

1534
01:41:15,686 --> 01:41:18,230
Well, he's gotta eat.
I mean, he's gotta have dinner.

1535
01:41:20,232 --> 01:41:22,443
[stammers] Okay, I'll tell you what.

1536
01:41:22,485 --> 01:41:24,612
Why don't we bring something
to his dressing room?

1537
01:41:24,653 --> 01:41:26,947
-John, show him a menu.
-[Dr Shirley] No.

1538
01:41:27,698 --> 01:41:29,742
I'm not eating in that storage room.

1539
01:41:31,410 --> 01:41:33,704
Okay, uh, well, if you prefer,

1540
01:41:33,746 --> 01:41:37,083
there's a very popular establishment
right down the road, the Orange Bird,

1541
01:41:37,124 --> 01:41:38,793
they'd be happy to feed you.

1542
01:41:38,834 --> 01:41:42,254
-[scoffs]
-Doc, come here.

1543
01:41:43,422 --> 01:41:45,174
-[laughs quietly]
-Just one second.

1544
01:41:46,592 --> 01:41:50,554
Maybe that other place is better anyway.
The dinner rolls here are like rocks.

1545
01:41:50,596 --> 01:41:53,432
You just go over and...
you go over and come back.

1546
01:41:58,229 --> 01:42:01,023
It's the last show.
It's the bottom of the ninth.

1547
01:42:01,065 --> 01:42:04,610
Let's just get it over with and we can
go home and get away from these pricks.

1548
01:42:05,694 --> 01:42:06,654
Huh?

1549
01:42:06,695 --> 01:42:10,491
Ah, there you go.
The fish is wonderful tonight.

1550
01:42:16,539 --> 01:42:18,165
Either I eat in this room...

1551
01:42:19,375 --> 01:42:21,168
or I'm not performing tonight.

1552
01:42:25,673 --> 01:42:27,967
May I have a word with <i>you</i>?

1553
01:42:33,013 --> 01:42:34,682
[sighs] No.

1554
01:42:40,438 --> 01:42:44,817
[sighs] Mr Villanueva,
you have to talk sense to Mr Shirley.

1555
01:42:44,859 --> 01:42:47,862
Please make him understand,
we're not insulting him personally.

1556
01:42:47,903 --> 01:42:49,905
This is just the way
things are done down here.

1557
01:42:49,947 --> 01:42:51,907
Yeah, well, he's not from down here.

1558
01:42:51,949 --> 01:42:54,118
Yeah, just, just ask him to be reasonable.

1559
01:42:54,160 --> 01:42:56,829
I got 400 guests in there
expecting to be entertained tonight.

1560
01:42:56,871 --> 01:42:59,081
And Dr Shirley expects to eat tonight.

1561
01:42:59,123 --> 01:43:01,500
Why can't you just make an exception
this one time?

1562
01:43:03,335 --> 01:43:05,713
Let me tell you a story. [clears throat]

1563
01:43:05,755 --> 01:43:09,008
You ever hear of
the Boston Celtics basketball club?

1564
01:43:09,049 --> 01:43:11,469
-Yeah.
-Well, those boys came through here

1565
01:43:11,510 --> 01:43:13,721
couple years ago on a barnstorming tour,

1566
01:43:13,763 --> 01:43:16,474
and seeing as they was
the world champions of the league and all,

1567
01:43:16,515 --> 01:43:20,019
we were tickled to have them here,
and we rolled out the welcome wagon.

1568
01:43:20,060 --> 01:43:23,022
So do you know what table
their big coon ate at that night?

1569
01:43:24,815 --> 01:43:26,984
-No.
-I don't either.

1570
01:43:27,026 --> 01:43:28,736
But it wasn't one of ours.

1571
01:43:28,778 --> 01:43:32,740
Now, let's cut the bullshit.
Tell me what it's gonna take, huh?

1572
01:43:32,782 --> 01:43:35,326
Say, uh, $100, you get your boy to play?

1573
01:43:37,745 --> 01:43:39,288
You think you can buy me?

1574
01:43:39,330 --> 01:43:41,373
[chuckles] With all due respect, sir,

1575
01:43:41,415 --> 01:43:44,085
you wouldn't be in a job like this
if you couldn't be bought.

1576
01:43:44,126 --> 01:43:47,004
-[Mr Kindell grunts]
-[Dr Shirley] Stop. Tony.

1577
01:43:49,381 --> 01:43:50,508
It's all right.

1578
01:43:53,135 --> 01:43:54,261
I'll play...

1579
01:43:55,638 --> 01:43:57,181
if you want me to.

1580
01:43:59,767 --> 01:44:02,353
[soft music fades in]

1581
01:44:11,487 --> 01:44:13,614
All right. Let's get the fuck out of here.

1582
01:44:14,949 --> 01:44:17,368
What do you mean "let's get out of here"?

1583
01:44:17,409 --> 01:44:19,453
Where the hell do you think you're going?

1584
01:44:19,495 --> 01:44:21,747
Don, don't do this.
Now, you signed a contract

1585
01:44:21,789 --> 01:44:24,125
and I know you're the kind of man
who honors a contract.

1586
01:44:24,166 --> 01:44:26,168
Connie, Bill, everything's gonna be fine.

1587
01:44:26,210 --> 01:44:28,838
You got a show to do, mister!
You turn yourself around

1588
01:44:28,879 --> 01:44:31,215
right now, goddamn it! Right now!

1589
01:44:31,966 --> 01:44:34,176
This is why you people
don't work down here.

1590
01:44:34,218 --> 01:44:36,095
Cos you're unreliable, you hear me?

1591
01:44:36,137 --> 01:44:39,140
I shipped that goddamn Steinway
in from Atlanta for you!

1592
01:44:46,689 --> 01:44:47,565
Tony?

1593
01:44:48,482 --> 01:44:49,817
Are you hungry?

1594
01:44:49,859 --> 01:44:52,403
Does Betty like butta-er?

1595
01:44:53,821 --> 01:44:55,990
[laughs]

1596
01:44:56,031 --> 01:44:59,285
-[man] One, two...
-[drumsticks clicking]

1597
01:44:59,326 --> 01:45:01,454
[upbeat live music and chatter]

1598
01:45:37,114 --> 01:45:40,117
-You a cop?
-Do I look Irish?

1599
01:45:41,285 --> 01:45:42,536
What you want, baby?

1600
01:45:42,578 --> 01:45:45,414
-Two Cutty Sarks, neat.
-Coming up.

1601
01:45:52,671 --> 01:45:55,341
Mm. Whatever your specialty is,
we'll take it.

1602
01:45:56,675 --> 01:45:58,469
Two Orange Birds!

1603
01:46:06,102 --> 01:46:08,687
[band music ends]

1604
01:46:11,065 --> 01:46:14,693
I like what you did back there, Doc.
You stood up for yourself.

1605
01:46:17,196 --> 01:46:21,158
It's like what your friend,
the President, said: "Ask not...

1606
01:46:22,910 --> 01:46:27,248
your country what you can do for it.
Ask what you do for yourself."

1607
01:46:29,041 --> 01:46:30,084
You know?

1608
01:46:32,711 --> 01:46:36,799
So, darling...
what you do all dressed up like that?

1609
01:46:37,466 --> 01:46:39,802
-Nothing particularly important.
-[scoffs]

1610
01:46:40,886 --> 01:46:43,431
-Shouldn't judge a man by his clothes.
-[Tony chuckles]

1611
01:46:43,472 --> 01:46:46,851
He's only the greatest
piano player in the world.

1612
01:46:46,892 --> 01:46:49,520
That right? You good?

1613
01:46:49,562 --> 01:46:53,566
-[chuckles]
-Don't be shy, Doc. Tell her who you are.

1614
01:46:53,607 --> 01:46:56,569
Don't tell me nothing. Show me.

1615
01:46:59,238 --> 01:47:00,906
[bartender chuckles]

1616
01:47:02,908 --> 01:47:04,326
Come on.

1617
01:47:13,127 --> 01:47:14,420
[Tony chuckles]

1618
01:47:20,801 --> 01:47:23,012
[chatter]

1619
01:47:36,150 --> 01:47:37,485
[laughs]

1620
01:47:43,407 --> 01:47:46,202
[plays "Winter Wind" by Chopin]

1621
01:48:05,971 --> 01:48:08,557
[music intensifies]

1622
01:48:41,841 --> 01:48:43,717
[stops playing]

1623
01:48:43,759 --> 01:48:46,512
[cheering and applause]

1624
01:48:49,598 --> 01:48:50,808
Whoo!

1625
01:48:51,517 --> 01:48:54,186
[Tony] Yeah! Yeah!

1626
01:49:01,694 --> 01:49:04,947
[lively blues music]

1627
01:50:21,482 --> 01:50:23,609
[music fades out]

1628
01:50:23,651 --> 01:50:25,528
That's how you break a key.

1629
01:50:25,569 --> 01:50:27,404
[both laughing]

1630
01:50:27,947 --> 01:50:31,659
Oh, that was a good time.
I'd do that once a month for free.

1631
01:50:31,700 --> 01:50:34,286
-You were unbelievable.
-Hey, Tony.

1632
01:50:35,162 --> 01:50:38,541
-I bet if we leave now, we can make it.
-Make what?

1633
01:50:38,582 --> 01:50:41,127
[Dr Shirley]
Christmas Eve, in New York City.

1634
01:50:44,505 --> 01:50:45,589
[two gunshots]

1635
01:50:45,631 --> 01:50:46,924
[man] Oh, shit!

1636
01:50:48,050 --> 01:50:49,760
[grunts]

1637
01:50:49,802 --> 01:50:51,178
[dog barking]

1638
01:50:57,518 --> 01:51:00,062
Don't ever flash
your wad of cash in a bar.

1639
01:51:10,156 --> 01:51:12,032
I knew you had a gun.

1640
01:51:12,074 --> 01:51:15,536
["Your Replacement is Here" by Edd Henry]
<i>♪ No more heartaches </i>♪

1641
01:51:16,787 --> 01:51:19,457
<i>♪ And no more sorrow </i>♪

1642
01:51:20,374 --> 01:51:23,127
<i>♪ Everything's looking brighter </i>♪

1643
01:51:24,170 --> 01:51:27,214
<i>♪ For tomorrow </i>♪

1644
01:51:27,965 --> 01:51:30,760
<i>♪ So I guess I might as well </i>♪

1645
01:51:31,552 --> 01:51:34,555
<i>♪ Jump in right now, dear </i>♪

1646
01:51:34,972 --> 01:51:36,891
<i>♪ Baby, your replacement is here... </i>♪

1647
01:51:36,932 --> 01:51:38,434
This could get bad, Doc.

1648
01:51:39,477 --> 01:51:40,394
Yes.

1649
01:51:41,729 --> 01:51:44,440
It's a shame we don't have something
to protect us on our journey.

1650
01:51:44,482 --> 01:51:46,484
[clicks tongue] Oh, I know.

1651
01:51:46,525 --> 01:51:49,737
Why don't you put
your lucky rock up on the dash, Tony?

1652
01:51:52,323 --> 01:51:55,618
Come on, Tony.
We need all the help we can get.

1653
01:52:00,998 --> 01:52:02,041
Thank you.

1654
01:52:02,083 --> 01:52:03,959
I feel safer already.

1655
01:52:06,504 --> 01:52:08,923
You're a real prick, you know that?

1656
01:52:08,964 --> 01:52:11,008
[chuckles]

1657
01:52:13,385 --> 01:52:16,180
[soft ambient music]

1658
01:52:21,310 --> 01:52:23,354
[Tony sighs]

1659
01:52:30,236 --> 01:52:33,906
-[siren wailing]
-Ah, shit!

1660
01:52:37,243 --> 01:52:38,702
[Dr Shirley groans]

1661
01:52:43,624 --> 01:52:45,584
Goddamn cops.

1662
01:52:47,002 --> 01:52:50,256
[music intensifies]

1663
